%Andrea###2009-06-26 07:25:11###object###text###1.1.4.2
object(text,'1.1.4.2','JAPANESE WOODCUT-PRINTS AND I',[
id-26,
typeOfObject-'TEXT',
text_id-26,
txt-'1.1.4.2',
text_type-'',
text_category-'',
text_title_en-'JAPANESE WOODCUT-PRINTS AND I',
text_title_ge-'JAPANISCHE HOLZSCHNITTE UND ICH',
text_keywords-'japanischer Farbholzschnitt, japanese woodcut, Hokusai, Tokio, Tokyo, Hiroshige, Japan',
text_date-'1976-00-00',
text_summary_en-'',
text_summary_ge-'',
text_language-'en',
text_contents-'&lt;p style=&quot;line-height: 150%&quot; class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;The first time I came in contact with Japanese woodcut-prints was in Italy when I was hitchhiking with friends and I saw rainfalls of Hiroshige as some peasants walked with umbrellas in the rain, and I saw Hokusai prints with the Fujiyama in the background and with clouds and with water and waves, and this all left such a deep impression on me that I decided later to do prints.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style=&quot;line-height: 150%&quot; class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;Immediately I did some sketches for woodcut-prints - it was all in 1950. It took a very long time, ten years later, finally, when I was myself in &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;Tokyo&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt; I could contact the first Japanese woodcutters and it was very difficult to convince them to work together with an European artist, because they are very jealous of their art and it is right so.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style=&quot;line-height: 150%&quot; class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;We have woodcut-prints in &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;Europe&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt; too, but they are very rough and woody like peasents with bad manners and they are mostly in one colour, black. Though there has been a woodcut tradition in &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;Austria&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt; during the turn of the century it was an imitation under the influence of the Japanese woodcuts.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style=&quot;line-height: 150%&quot; class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt; &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style=&quot;line-height: 150%&quot; class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;Anyhow as it was possible for me to work together with Japanese woodcutters and printers, it was as if my work would get into new dimensions, into something much more valuable and precious than what I experienced with other techniques, i. e. lithography, silkscreen, etchings and engraving.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style=&quot;line-height: 150%&quot; class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt; &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style=&quot;line-height: 150%&quot; class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;There is something very light and very delightful about Japanese woodcuts, they seem to float in the air having the feeling as if you would look at water-colours. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;Japan&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt; is the high mountain of the woodcuts of the world. When I think of &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;Japan&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt; and when many people think of &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;Japan&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt; they think about Hokusai and Hiroshige.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style=&quot;line-height: 150%&quot; class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt; &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style=&quot;line-height: 150%&quot; class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;First because this is &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;Japan&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt; and it is such a pity that this art is dying out and that master-cutters and master-printers don&rsquo;t get pupils. I hope and believe that by working together with Japanese woodcut-printers I helped in a little tiny way to give new fruits to this noble art so it can survive and get another dimension.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style=&quot;line-height: 150%&quot; class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;I went one step further, I did not only ask the Japanese woodcutters to copy my paintings but I interfered with my own design which was then cut and printed so that the latest woodcuts are originals which were created in the process but they are pieces of art, but I must say, that all Japanese woodcuts, even if they are so to say copied after a painting, are not a reproduction at all because in the Japanese woodcuts there are three masters who work closely together, where it is not sure who is the best one - there is the artist, there is the cutter and there is the printer and these three men side by side cooperate to produce and create a masterpiece, and this is why all three masters should have, and do have their icons, their stamp on the finished woodcuts. The master of cutters sometimes changes the original design substantially. In order to put it into woodcut medium, he has to alter the lines and give them another harmony.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style=&quot;line-height: 150%&quot; class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt; &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style=&quot;line-height: 150%&quot; class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;I am very happy and very honoured that it was made possible for me, as I believe the first Western artist to be able to work together with Japanese woodcutters and printers and I hope I will not deceive them. I hope that my style is oriental any way, so that it is only a small step between me and &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;Japan&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;, because I think it would be difficult to cut for instance masters like Rembrandt and Raffael in wood. It must be somebody whose art is orientated towards the East.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style=&quot;line-height: 150%&quot; class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;It is like the flying seeds of the dandelion who flies far over the seas, they fly and get new dandelions. The clouds go here and they go there and they go far over the seas. They fly over the Pacific and &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;America&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt; and the &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;Atlantic&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;. They take root far away from their home country and the new seeds fly back. This is what I want to be. I want to bring back to &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;Japan&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt; the fruit of the wonderful SEED &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;Japan&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt; has planted into the world and the tree has grown in the meantime and has changed colour and form. This is my gratitude and my thanksgiving to &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;Japan&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;, I hope it will be accepted.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;',
text_contents_en-'&lt;p style=&quot;line-height: 150%&quot; class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;The first time I came in contact with Japanese woodcut-prints was in Italy when I was hitchhiking with friends and I saw rainfalls of Hiroshige as some peasants walked with umbrellas in the rain, and I saw Hokusai prints with the Fujiyama in the background and with clouds and with water and waves, and this all left such a deep impression on me that I decided later to do prints.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style=&quot;line-height: 150%&quot; class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;Immediately I did some sketches for woodcut-prints - it was all in 1950. It took a very long time, ten years later, finally, when I was myself in &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;Tokyo&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt; I could contact the first Japanese woodcutters and it was very difficult to convince them to work together with an European artist, because they are very jealous of their art and it is right so.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style=&quot;line-height: 150%&quot; class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;We have woodcut-prints in &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;Europe&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt; too, but they are very rough and woody like peasents with bad manners and they are mostly in one colour, black. Though there has been a woodcut tradition in &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;Austria&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt; during the turn of the century it was an imitation under the influence of the Japanese woodcuts.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style=&quot;line-height: 150%&quot; class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt; &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style=&quot;line-height: 150%&quot; class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;Anyhow as it was possible for me to work together with Japanese woodcutters and printers, it was as if my work would get into new dimensions, into something much more valuable and precious than what I experienced with other techniques, i. e. lithography, silkscreen, etchings and engraving.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style=&quot;line-height: 150%&quot; class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt; &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style=&quot;line-height: 150%&quot; class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;There is something very light and very delightful about Japanese woodcuts, they seem to float in the air having the feeling as if you would look at water-colours. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;Japan&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt; is the high mountain of the woodcuts of the world. When I think of &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;Japan&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt; and when many people think of &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;Japan&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt; they think about Hokusai and Hiroshige.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style=&quot;line-height: 150%&quot; class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt; &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style=&quot;line-height: 150%&quot; class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;First because this is &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;Japan&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt; and it is such a pity that this art is dying out and that master-cutters and master-printers don&rsquo;t get pupils. I hope and believe that by working together with Japanese woodcut-printers I helped in a little tiny way to give new fruits to this noble art so it can survive and get another dimension.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style=&quot;line-height: 150%&quot; class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;I went one step further, I did not only ask the Japanese woodcutters to copy my paintings but I interfered with my own design which was then cut and printed so that the latest woodcuts are originals which were created in the process but they are pieces of art, but I must say, that all Japanese woodcuts, even if they are so to say copied after a painting, are not a reproduction at all because in the Japanese woodcuts there are three masters who work closely together, where it is not sure who is the best one - there is the artist, there is the cutter and there is the printer and these three men side by side cooperate to produce and create a masterpiece, and this is why all three masters should have, and do have their icons, their stamp on the finished woodcuts. The master of cutters sometimes changes the original design substantially. In order to put it into woodcut medium, he has to alter the lines and give them another harmony.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style=&quot;line-height: 150%&quot; class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt; &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style=&quot;line-height: 150%&quot; class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;I am very happy and very honoured that it was made possible for me, as I believe the first Western artist to be able to work together with Japanese woodcutters and printers and I hope I will not deceive them. I hope that my style is oriental any way, so that it is only a small step between me and &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;Japan&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;, because I think it would be difficult to cut for instance masters like Rembrandt and Raffael in wood. It must be somebody whose art is orientated towards the East.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style=&quot;line-height: 150%&quot; class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;It is like the flying seeds of the dandelion who flies far over the seas, they fly and get new dandelions. The clouds go here and they go there and they go far over the seas. They fly over the Pacific and &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;America&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt; and the &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;Atlantic&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;. They take root far away from their home country and the new seeds fly back. This is what I want to be. I want to bring back to &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;Japan&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt; the fruit of the wonderful SEED &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;Japan&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt; has planted into the world and the tree has grown in the meantime and has changed colour and form. This is my gratitude and my thanksgiving to &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;Japan&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; line-height: 150%&quot;&gt;, I hope it will be accepted.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;',
text_contents_ge-'  &lt;p class=&quot;11dtbodycheltconbook&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Mit japanischen Holzschnitten kam ich zum ersten Mal in Ber&uuml;hrung, als ich mit Freunden durch Italien trampte. Ich sah, wie bei Hiroshige Bauern mit Regenschirmen durch den Regen liefen, und ich sah Holzschnitte von Hokusai, mit dem Fudschijama im Hintergrund und mit Wolken, Wasser und Wellen. All das hat bei mir einen so tiefen Eindruck hinterlassen, da&szlig; ich sp&auml;ter beschlo&szlig;, selbst Drucke zu gestalten.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p class=&quot;11dtbodycheltconbook&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p class=&quot;11dtbodycheltconbook&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Unmittelbar danach zeichnete ich einige Skizzen f&uuml;r Holzschnitte &lt;span style=&quot;letter-spacing: 0.25pt&quot;&gt;&ndash; all das geschah 1950. Es dauerte noch sehr lange, zehn Jahre, &lt;/span&gt;bis ich endlich selbst nach Tokio kam und mit den ersten japanischen Holzschneidern Kontakt aufnehmen konnte. Es war &auml;u&szlig;erst schwierig, sie davon zu &uuml;berzeugen, mit einem europ&auml;ischen K&uuml;nstler zusammenzuarbeiten, weil sie zu Recht sehr eifers&uuml;chtig &uuml;ber ihre Kunst wachen.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p class=&quot;11dtbodycheltconbook&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p class=&quot;11dtbodycheltconbook&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Wir haben auch in Europa Holzschnitte, aber die sind sehr derb und h&ouml;lzern, z.B. Darstellungen von Bauern mit schlechten Manieren, und sie sind meistens in nur einer Farbe gehalten, in Schwarz. Obwohl es zur Jahrhundertwende in &Ouml;sterreich eine Tradition des Holzschnitts gab, war sie doch nur eine Imitation unter dem Einflu&szlig; japanischer Holzschnitte.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p class=&quot;11dtbodycheltconbook&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p class=&quot;11dtbodycheltconbook&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Als ich dann die M&ouml;glichkeit bekam, mit japanischen Holzschneidern und Druckern zusammenzuarbeiten, war es auf jeden Fall f&uuml;r mich, als h&auml;tte meine Arbeit neue Dimensionen erreicht. Sie erschien mir wertvoller und kostbarer als die Arbeit mit anderen Techniken, wie Lithographie, Siebdruck und Radierung.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p class=&quot;11dtbodycheltconbook&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p class=&quot;11dtbodycheltconbook&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Japanischen Holzschnitten haftet etwas ausgesprochen Lichtes und Zauberhaftes an, sie scheinen, wie mit Aquarellfarben gemalt, in der Luft zu schweben. Japan ist weltweit die Hochburg des Holzschnitts. Wenn ich an Japan denke, denke ich wie viele Menschen an Hokusai und Hiroshige.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p class=&quot;11dtbodycheltconbook&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p class=&quot;11dtbodycheltconbook&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Diese Namen stehen f&uuml;r Japan, und ich finde es sehr bedauerlich, da&szlig; diese Kunst im Aussterben begriffen ist und die Holzschnitt- und Druckmeister keine Sch&uuml;ler mehr finden. Ich hoffe und glaube, da&szlig; ich durch meine Zusammenarbeit mit japanischen Meistern des Holzschnitts ein wenig dazu beigetragen habe, dieser noblen Kunst einen neuen Impuls zu geben, so da&szlig; sie &uuml;berleben und weitergetragen werden kann.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p class=&quot;11dtbodycheltconbook&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p class=&quot;11dtbodycheltconbook&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Ich ging noch einen Schritt weiter. Ich habe nicht nur japanische Holzschneider gebeten, meine Bilder zu kopieren, sondern habe meine eigenen Entw&uuml;rfe eingebracht, die dann geschnitten und gedruckt wurden, so da&szlig; es sich bei den letzten Holzschnitten um Originale handelt, die im Schaffensproze&szlig; entstanden und somit eigenst&auml;ndige Kunstwerke sind. Aber ich mu&szlig; hinzuf&uuml;gen, da&szlig; es sich bei s&auml;mtlichen japanischen Holzschnitten, selbst wenn sie sozusagen die Kopie eines Gem&auml;ldes sind, ganz und gar nicht um Reproduktionen handelt, weil beim japanischen Holzschnitt drei Meister beteiligt sind, die eng zusammenarbeiten, und man nie sicher sagen kann, wer der beste ist &ndash; da sind der Maler, der Holzschneider und der Drucker, und diese drei Personen wirken Seite an Seite, um ein Meisterwerk hervorzubringen und zu schaffen. Deshalb sollten, und genauso ist es auch, alle drei Meister ihre Signatur, ihren Stempel, auf dem fertigen Holzschnitt hinterlassen. Ein Meister des Holzschnitts gestaltet manchmal den urspr&uuml;nglichen Entwurf von Grund auf um. Er mu&szlig; die Linien ver&auml;ndern und ihnen eine andere Harmonie verleihen, wenn er sie in das Medium Holz umsetzen will.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p class=&quot;11dtbodycheltconbook&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p class=&quot;11dtbodycheltconbook&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Ich bin sehr gl&uuml;cklich und f&uuml;hle mich sehr geehrt, da&szlig; es mir als, wie ich glaube, einzigem westlichen K&uuml;nstler, erm&ouml;glicht wurde, mit japanischen Holzschneidern und Druckern zusammenzuarbeiten, und ich hoffe, ich werde sie nicht entt&auml;uschen. Ich hoffe, da&szlig; mein Stil ohnehin &ouml;stlich ist, so da&szlig; zwischen Japan und mir keine allzu gro&szlig;e Kluft besteht. Ich glaube n&auml;mlich, da&szlig; es schwierig w&auml;re, Meister wie Rembrandt und Raffael in Holz zu schneiden. Es mu&szlig; jemand sein, dessen Kunst auf den Osten gerichtet ist.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p class=&quot;11dtbodycheltconbook&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p class=&quot;11dtbodycheltconbook&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Es ist wie mit den Samen des L&ouml;wenzahns, die weit &uuml;ber die Meere fliegen und neuen L&ouml;wenzahn hervorbringen. Wie die Wolken sind sie einmal hier und einmal dort, fliegen weit &uuml;ber das Meer, fliegen &uuml;ber den Pazifik, &uuml;ber Amerika und den Atlantik. Weit von ihrem Heimatland schlagen sie Wurzeln, und neue Samen fliegen zur&uuml;ck. Genau das m&ouml;chte ich sein. Ich m&ouml;chte Japan die Frucht des wundervollen Samenkorns zur&uuml;ckbringen, das es in die Welt gepflanzt hat. Der Baum ist in der Zwischenzeit gewachsen und hat seine Farbe und seine Form ge&auml;ndert. Mit dieser Gabe bringe ich meine Dankbarkeit Japan gegen&uuml;ber zum Ausdruck und ich hoffe, sie wird angenommen.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  ',
text_occasion_en-'Written in 1977.&lt;br /&gt;',
text_occasion_ge-'Geschrieben in Wien 1976.&lt;br /&gt;',
text_published_en-'&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;David Kung (Ed.): The Woodcut Works of Hundertwasser 1960-1975. Gruener Janura AG: Glarus, 1977&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt; &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Catalogue of the World Travelling Museum Exhibition 1975&ndash;1987: &lt;u&gt;English edition:&lt;/u&gt; Tel Aviv, Reykjavik, 1976; Cape Town, Pretoria, Rio de Janeiro, S&atilde;o Paulo, Brasilia, Caracas, 1977; Mexico City, Toronto, 1978; Rome, H&oslash;vikodden, 1980; Helsinki, 1981; London, 1983. pp. 279-282&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt; &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Schmied, Wieland (ed.): Hundertwasser 1928&ndash;2000, Catalogue Raisonn&eacute;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Vol. II: F&uuml;rst, Andrea Christa: Catalogue Raisonn&eacute;. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Taschen: &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Cologne&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;, 2002, pp. 743-744 (German and English)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt; &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Schurian, Walter (ed.): Hundertwasser &ndash; Sch&ouml;ne Wege, Gedanken &uuml;ber Kunst und Leben. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;(Beautiful Paths &ndash; Thoughts on Art and Life) Langen M&uuml;ller Verlag: &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Munich&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;, 2004, pp. 89-91 (German)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;',
text_published_ge-'  &lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;David Kung (Hg.): The Woodcut Works of Hundertwasser 1960-1975. Gruener Janura AG: Glarus, 1977 (Englisch)&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Katalog zur Welt-Wanderausstellung 1975&ndash;1987: &lt;u&gt;Englische Ausgabe:&lt;/u&gt; Tel Aviv, Reykjavik, 1976; Cape Town, Pretoria, Rio de Janeiro, S&atilde;o Paulo, Brasilia, Caracas, 1977; Mexiko City, Toronto, 1978; Rom, H&oslash;vikodden, 1980; Helsinki, 1981; London, 1983. &lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Schmied, Wieland (Hg.): Hundertwasser 1928&ndash;2000, Catalogue Raisonn&eacute; / Werkverzeichnis.&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Vol. II: F&uuml;rst, Andrea Christa: Catalogue Raisonn&eacute; / Werkverzeichnis. Taschen: K&ouml;ln 2002, S. 743-744 (Deutsch und Englisch)&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Schurian, Walter (Hg.): Hundertwasser &ndash; Sch&ouml;ne Wege, Gedanken &uuml;ber Kunst und Leben. Langen M&uuml;ller Verlag: M&uuml;nchen 2004, S. 89-91&lt;/p&gt;  ',
