%Andrea###2009-06-26 07:25:11###object###text###1.1.5.1.1
object(text,'1.1.5.1.1','On Transautomatism',[
id-86,
typeOfObject-'TEXT',
text_id-86,
txt-'1.1.5.1.1',
text_type-'',
text_category-'',
text_title_en-'On Transautomatism',
text_title_ge-'Zum Transautomatismus',
text_keywords-'Transautomatismus, Avantgarde, Theorie, Wahrnehmung, transautomatism, avant-garde, theory, perception, modern art, Moderne Kunst, Automatismus, automatism',
text_date-'2000-00-00',
text_summary_en-'',
text_summary_ge-'',
text_language-'en',
text_contents-'&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;In the mid-1950s, Hundertwasser grappled intensively with the development and function of modern art. He published a number of writings, clarifying and explaining his own position. In these theoretical writings, Hundertwasser identified in principle with the entire spectrum of the artistic activity at that time. Indeed, he felt that he was at the vanguard of the avant-garde: with &ldquo;Transautomatism&rdquo;, he believed he had transcended the automatism of Tachism and Informalism and had reached an ultimate point which could not be surpassed, a vantage point from which all developments and endeavours could be surveyed and arranged into a meaningful whole. For Hundertwasser, therefore, &ldquo;Transautomatism&rdquo; did not mean the subconscious, but a &raquo;departure towards true creativity&laquo; after the end of Tachism (which at that time was thought to be synonymous with &lt;em&gt;&eacute;criture automatique&lt;/em&gt; &ndash; automatic writing).&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;...&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Hundertwasser&rsquo;s main premise was that what we call &raquo;seeing&laquo; is not a highly developed sense, that we are actually illiterate in the visual sphere and that in general we only see and perceive what we have already seen before. Therefore, it is the task of modern art to teach people how to see new things in an entirely new way. The more capable a work of art is of serving this purpose, the higher it ranks.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;',
text_contents_en-'&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;In the mid-1950s, Hundertwasser grappled intensively with the development and function of modern art. He published a number of writings, clarifying and explaining his own position. In these theoretical writings, Hundertwasser identified in principle with the entire spectrum of the artistic activity at that time. Indeed, he felt that he was at the vanguard of the avant-garde: with &ldquo;Transautomatism&rdquo;, he believed he had transcended the automatism of Tachism and Informalism and had reached an ultimate point which could not be surpassed, a vantage point from which all developments and endeavours could be surveyed and arranged into a meaningful whole. For Hundertwasser, therefore, &ldquo;Transautomatism&rdquo; did not mean the subconscious, but a &raquo;departure towards true creativity&laquo; after the end of Tachism (which at that time was thought to be synonymous with &lt;em&gt;&eacute;criture automatique&lt;/em&gt; &ndash; automatic writing).&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;...&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Hundertwasser&rsquo;s main premise was that what we call &raquo;seeing&laquo; is not a highly developed sense, that we are actually illiterate in the visual sphere and that in general we only see and perceive what we have already seen before. Therefore, it is the task of modern art to teach people how to see new things in an entirely new way. The more capable a work of art is of serving this purpose, the higher it ranks.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;',
text_contents_ge-'  &lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Mitte der 50er Jahre hat sich Hundertwasser intensiv mit Entwicklung und Funktion der modernen Kunst auseinandergesetzt und eine Reihe von Texten zur Kl&auml;rung und Erkl&auml;rung des eigenen Standorts ver&ouml;ffentlicht. In diesen theoretischen Schriften identifizierte sich Hundertwasser prinzipiell mit der ganzen Breite der damals aktuellen k&uuml;nstlerischen Szene, ja er sah die eigene Position an der Spitze der Avantgarde: mit dem &quot;Transautomatismus&quot; seiner Malerei meint er, &uuml;ber den Automatismus der Tachis&shy;ten und Informellen hinauszugehen und einen letzt&shy;g&uuml;ltigen, nicht mehr &uuml;berholbaren Punkt erreicht zu haben, einen Platz, von dem aus sich alle Entwick&shy;lungen und Strebungen &uuml;berschauen lassen und zu einem sinnvollen Ganzen ordnen. &quot;Transautomatismus&quot; bedeutete f&uuml;r ihn also nicht das Unbewu&szlig;te, sondern einen &quot;Aufbruch in die wahre Sch&ouml;pfung&quot; nach dem Ende des Tachismus (der damals mit einer &lt;em&gt;&eacute;criture automatique&lt;/em&gt; gleichgesetzt wurde).&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;....&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Hundertwasser ging davon aus, da&szlig; das, was wir &bdquo;Sehen&ldquo; nennen, sehr wenig entwickelt ist, da&szlig; wir im Visuellen eigentlich Analphabeten sind, da&szlig; der Mensch im allgemeinen immer nur das sieht und wahrnimmt, was er schon fr&uuml;her gesehen hat, und da&szlig; es die Aufgabe der modernen Kunst ist, Neues sehen, ja &uuml;berhaupt neu sehen zu lehren. Der Stellenwert eines Kunstwerkes ist desto h&ouml;her anzusetzen, je mehr es diesem Ziel zu dienen vermag.&lt;/p&gt;  ',
text_occasion_en-'',
text_occasion_ge-'',
text_published_en-'',
text_published_ge-'',
text_author-'Wieland Schmied',
text_orig_lang-'',
text_translator-'',
text_source_en-'&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;&lt;font face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;&gt;Schmied, Wieland (ed.): Hundertwasser 1928&ndash;2000, Catalogue Raisonn&eacute;. &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;font face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Vol. I: Schmied, Wieland: Personality, Life, Work. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Taschen: Cologne, 2000, p. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;80&lt;p&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/span&gt;',
text_source_ge-'    &lt;p class=&quot;MsoFootnoteText&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 11pt&quot;&gt;Schmied, Wieland (Hg.): Hundertwasser 1928&ndash;2000, Catalogue Raisonn&eacute;.Vol. I: Schmied, Wieland: Pers&ouml;nlichkeit, Leben, Werk. Taschen: K&ouml;ln 2000, S.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 11pt&quot;&gt; 80 f.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  ',
text_excerpt-'',
text_origin-''
]).

%Andrea###2009-06-26 07:25:11###object###text###1.1.5.1.2
object(text,'1.1.5.1.2','On Transautomatism',[
id-87,
typeOfObject-'TEXT',
text_id-87,
txt-'1.1.5.1.2',
text_type-'',
text_category-'',
text_title_en-'On Transautomatism',
text_title_ge-'Zum Transautomatismus',
text_keywords-'Transautomatism, Transautomatismus, Wahrnehmung, perception',
text_date-'1998-00-00',
text_summary_en-'',
text_summary_ge-'',
text_language-'en',
text_contents-'&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;His theory of Transautomatism was both a criticism of the public&rsquo;s perceptive illiteracy and an affirmation of the necessity for the creative involvement of that public in the work of art.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;',
text_contents_en-'&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;His theory of Transautomatism was both a criticism of the public&rsquo;s perceptive illiteracy and an affirmation of the necessity for the creative involvement of that public in the work of art.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;',
text_contents_ge-'  &lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Seine Theorie des Transautomatismus war gleichzeitig eine Kritik am Wahrnehmungsanalphabetismus des Publikums und die Bejahung der Notwendigkeit der kreativen Beteiligung des Publikums am Kunstwerk.&lt;/p&gt;  ',
text_occasion_en-'',
text_occasion_ge-'',
text_published_en-'',
text_published_ge-'',
text_author-'Pierre Restany',
text_orig_lang-'',
text_translator-'',
text_source_en-'&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;&lt;font face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;&gt;Restany, Pierre: Hundertwasser &ndash; The Painter-King with the 5 Skins. Taschen: Cologne, 1998, p. 21&lt;p&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/span&gt;',
text_source_ge-'  &lt;p class=&quot;MsoFootnoteText&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 11pt&quot;&gt;Restany, Pierre: Hundertwasser &ndash; Der Maler-K&ouml;nig mit den f&uuml;nf H&auml;uten. Taschen: K&ouml;ln 1998, S. 21&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  ',
text_excerpt-'',
text_origin-''
]).

%Andrea###2009-06-26 07:25:11###object###text###1.1.5.1.3
object(text,'1.1.5.1.3','On Transautomatism',[
id-88,
typeOfObject-'TEXT',
text_id-88,
txt-'1.1.5.1.3',
text_type-'',
text_category-'',
text_title_en-'On Transautomatism',
text_title_ge-'Zum Transautomatismus',
text_keywords-'Transautomatismus, transautomatism, individual film, Individualfilm, Wahrnehmung, perception',
text_date-'2004-00-00',
text_summary_en-'',
text_summary_ge-'',
text_language-'en',
text_contents-'&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; letter-spacing: 0.3pt&quot;&gt;In this process, Hundertwasser explores multiple possibilities of communication between the artist, the object and the viewer. In this process, the viewer co-produces the artist&rsquo;s picture, completing it whenever he looks at it while the artist initiates an &ldquo;individual film&rdquo;, which subsequently unreels independently. The viewer watches everything which concerns himself, distinguishes him and is appropriate for him. Furthermore, he creates his own perspectives of the object, meeting up with the artist who responds, intimately connected with his creations.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; letter-spacing: 0.3pt&quot;&gt;...&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; letter-spacing: 0.3pt&quot;&gt;In this sense, Hundertwasser sees himself in the role of an arbitrator of meaning and perception. He sets in motion views and still pictures; the film can unreel inside the viewer. What the viewer eventually sees, what touches him, what carries him away, what he identifies with or whether he feels something along the way eludes the artist&rsquo;s function and participation. He has set in motion what is there to be seen. Where it leads to depends on and lies in each individual. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; letter-spacing: 0.2pt&quot;&gt;The viewer transforms from a spectator to a seer and from a seer to a creator.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;',
text_contents_en-'&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; letter-spacing: 0.3pt&quot;&gt;In this process, Hundertwasser explores multiple possibilities of communication between the artist, the object and the viewer. In this process, the viewer co-produces the artist&rsquo;s picture, completing it whenever he looks at it while the artist initiates an &ldquo;individual film&rdquo;, which subsequently unreels independently. The viewer watches everything which concerns himself, distinguishes him and is appropriate for him. Furthermore, he creates his own perspectives of the object, meeting up with the artist who responds, intimately connected with his creations.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; letter-spacing: 0.3pt&quot;&gt;...&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; letter-spacing: 0.3pt&quot;&gt;In this sense, Hundertwasser sees himself in the role of an arbitrator of meaning and perception. He sets in motion views and still pictures; the film can unreel inside the viewer. What the viewer eventually sees, what touches him, what carries him away, what he identifies with or whether he feels something along the way eludes the artist&rsquo;s function and participation. He has set in motion what is there to be seen. Where it leads to depends on and lies in each individual. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; letter-spacing: 0.2pt&quot;&gt;The viewer transforms from a spectator to a seer and from a seer to a creator.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;',
text_contents_ge-'  &lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;letter-spacing: 0.3pt&quot;&gt;Hundertwasser macht in diesem Proze&szlig; vielf&auml;ltige M&ouml;glichkeiten der Mitteilungen zwischen dem K&uuml;nstler, dem Gegenstand und dem Betrachter aus. In ihm schafft der Betrachter das Bild des K&uuml;nstlers jeweils mit, er vollendet es bei jeder Betrachtung. Der K&uuml;nstler setzt dabei einen &raquo;Individualfilm&laquo; in Gang, der sich in der Folge selbst&auml;ndig abspult. Der Betrachter erblickt alles, was ihm selber zuf&auml;llt, was ihn auszeichnet, was ihm angemessen ist. Er schafft dar&uuml;ber hinaus seine eigenen Ausblicke in die Richtung des Gegenstands. Dort trifft er sich wieder mit dem K&uuml;nstler. Dieser antwortet. Er steht in einer innigen Verbindung zu seinen Sch&ouml;pfungen.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;letter-spacing: 0.3pt&quot;&gt;...&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;letter-spacing: 0.3pt&quot;&gt;So sieht sich Hundertwasser in einer Rolle als Sinn- und Wahrnehmungsvermittler: Er setzt Anschauungen und Standbilder in Bewegung; der Film kann abrollen, im Inneren des Betrachters. Was dieser dann sieht, wovon er anger&uuml;hrt wird, was ihn mitrei&szlig;t, womit er sich identifiziert und ob er dabei Gef&uuml;hle hegt, all dies entzieht sich dann der Aufgabe und des Mitspiels des K&uuml;nstlers. Er hat in Bewegung gesetzt, was es zu sehen gibt. Wohin es f&uuml;hrt, das liegt an und in jedem Einzelnen. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;letter-spacing: 0.2pt&quot;&gt;Der Betrachter wandelt sich vom Zuschauer zum Seher und vom Seher zum Sch&ouml;pfer.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  ',
text_occasion_en-'',
text_occasion_ge-'',
text_published_en-'',
text_published_ge-'',
text_author-'Walter Schurian',
text_orig_lang-'',
text_translator-'',
text_source_en-'&lt;font face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Schurian, Walter (ed.): Hundertwasser &ndash; Sch&ouml;ne Wege, Gedanken &uuml;ber Kunst und Leben (Beautiful Paths, Thoughts on Art and Life). &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Langen M&uuml;ller Verlag: Munich, 2004, p. 297-298&lt;p&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;',
text_source_ge-'&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 11pt&quot;&gt;Schurian, Walter (Hg.): Hundertwasser &ndash; Sch&ouml;ne Wege, Gedanken &uuml;ber Kunst und Leben.Langen M&uuml;ller Verlag: M&uuml;nchen 2004, S. 297 f.&lt;/span&gt;',
text_excerpt-'',
text_origin-''
]).

