]).

%Andrea###2009-06-26 07:25:11###object###text###1.1.5.4
object(text,'1.1.5.4','TAPE-RECORDED LETTER BY HUNDERTWASSER 
TO THE STUDENTS OF THE MASTER SCHOOL AT THE ACADEMY OF FINE ARTS IN VIENNA, MAY 1982
',[
id-73,
typeOfObject-'TEXT',
text_id-73,
txt-'1.1.5.4',
text_type-5,
text_category-'',
text_title_en-'TAPE-RECORDED LETTER BY HUNDERTWASSER 
TO THE STUDENTS OF THE MASTER SCHOOL AT THE ACADEMY OF FINE ARTS IN VIENNA, MAY 1982
',
text_title_ge-'TONBANDBRIEF HUNDERTWASSERS AN DIE STUDENTEN DER MEISTERSCHULE AN DER AKADEMIE DER BILDENDEN K&Uuml;NSTE IN WIEN VOM MAI 1982',
text_keywords-'Akademie, Kunst, Natur, Sch&ouml;pfung, Kreativit&auml;t, Gott, Material, Farbe, Pinsel, Skizze, &Ouml;kologie, Doerner, Chassis, Staffelei, Kreislauf, Friedensvertrag mit der Natur, academy, art, natur, creation, creativity, God, material, paint, brush, sketch, ecology, easel, circuit, Peace Treaty with Nature',
text_date-'1982-05-00',
text_summary_en-'',
text_summary_ge-'',
text_language-'en',
text_contents-'&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Dear Friends,&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Today is May 12, 1982. I am in New Zealand.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;It is already pretty cold here by now, May being about what November is in Europe. It is now a quarter past ten in the &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;evening; in Vienna it is a quarter past noon. Here everything is the other way round. Here you see the Southern Cross, warmth comes from the north, cold from the south. You are surely wondering why I am staying away so long, but the main reason for it is that I don&rsquo;t think one can learn anything at the Academy; only the weak go to the Academy; only the weak think they can study art, that they can learn art. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Either you have it in you like an inspiration which suddenly comes, or you look and look and usually don&rsquo;t find it. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Either you have the gifts you have been endowed with already as a child, from birth, or you don&rsquo;t. But if you have these gifts, you run the greatest risk at the Academy or at any school or any association with other people of losing the most precious of all the assets in your possession: of losing your own self. But if you have not found your own self or have lost it and want to recover it, the Academy is the worst possible place. For there you are exposed to influences which do not fit you, and there is a very great danger of adopting something which you then imagine to be yourself, as it were, that you recognise yourself in the knowledge and actions of other people, that you identify with something that is not yourself, with something you would like to be but aren&rsquo;t and then suffer from it all your life. It is as if you had put on a false skin or donned clothes which don&rsquo;t fit and now wanted to grow into these clothes, so to speak.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;That is why I told you at the outset, as you&rsquo;ll recall, to bring in your own childhood drawings. Everyone should begin at the point where he was still himself, before he was inundated, before he was alienated, by his parental home, by the system of upbringing, by school, by the customary ways of our civilisation. For one can only continue building from the ground up. That is the only solid, secure, unshakeable basis, one&rsquo;s own origins. It is irrelevant what these childhood drawings look like. One can only build on this basis; otherwise it is a castle in the air, a house of cards which will collapse. You can&rsquo;t build by putting heavy bricks on flimsy matchboxes.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Since you of course don&rsquo;t want to go home &ndash; just as I experienced once before, when I taught briefly in Hamburg &ndash; I want each of you to remember who you are by having your own berth, your own world, your own house in the Master School, where you come into as little contact as possible with what is around you. You should then regard this berth, this world, as your origin, around which everything will be built. That is the centre of activity, so to speak. This berth should be closed off from external influences, from influences of your neighbours and in particular from my own influence. For nothing is more dangerous than to try to subject yourself to my influence, to the influence of the master, in the parlance of the Master School. That is extremely dangerous. You must go your own way, and I must stress once again: if anyone paints similarly to the way I do, or even vaguely approaches it, he must leave; then there is just no point to it. For me it is embarrassing, and for the person who does it, it is a death sentence.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;The next question is why I put trees in the classrooms. It is perfectly clear: art and nature have a lot to do with one another. Art is the bridge between man and nature. Art is not the bridge between people. What art is, must be worked out by everyone for himself in a dialogue with nature. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Man cannot be creative the way creation was, the way God creates trees, nature, plants, brings forth flowers, brings forth worlds which then go on existing of their own accord and, thanks to an incredible diversity, have a raison d&rsquo;&ecirc;tre of their own and form an interlinking clockwork: man cannot do that, no matter how much he exerts his intellect. On the contrary, the harder he exerts his intellect, the less progress is made. Man only makes progress when he lets other things work, apart from his intellect. His intellect should only be a cause for him to control himself, but not to be haughty towards nature. Man achieves nothing by force; the artist, in particular, achieves nothing by force. The era when the artist was a dictator is coming to a close. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;The artist can only be a mediator between man and nature if he has special antennae, if he is a medium, as it were, a receiving station, if he can listen, if he can be a tool for this certain something which comes from somewhere else. If he can throw open gates to another, better, more beautiful world, to a more genuine world. And that is a parallel world. That is a world which we sometimes get hold of in dreams. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Of course it would be completely wrong, in turn, to take drugs to reach that world. You don&rsquo;t reach that world with drugs, and if you did, it wouldn&rsquo;t do you any good because you would destroy yourself in the process. You can only enter that world with the full consciousness of your spiritual powers and as a go-between, that is to say as a very gentle, careful listener. If one has observed and listened well, with humility, so to speak, then it is possible to know that world and impart that fantastic world which is inside one and also all around one, and when one gets hold of that world, one is overwhelmed by a feeling of great happiness. Then one feels not only satisfied with oneself &ndash; for painting is not only a self-healing activity, after all &ndash; but should in addition also be able to have an effect on other people. But if one wants to arrive at greater truth in larger dimensions, one which also concerns other people, one has to listen more deeply, of course, and set one&rsquo;s own ego aside, put one&rsquo;s own intellect even further away &ndash; but not criticism of oneself. Dal&iacute; said a very good thing: &ldquo;la m&eacute;thode paranoya critique&rdquo;, that is, one should be abnormal, but at the same time have a self-critical attitude towards this abnormality. This seeming contradiction is very important in painting, however. On the one hand one should and must let oneself go, drift and flow, as it were, the way a cloud drifts along and a river flows, and the way the grass grows and a flower opens up; on the other hand one must be critical of oneself.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;As art is a bridge between man and nature, it is of utmost importance that one compares what one does with the achievements, with the creativity of nature. If what one does oneself can withstand a comparison with nature, comparison with a leaf, with a tree, then one can be very content. The growth of plants is an amazing thing. The plants yawn and stretch, wrinkle their leaves if something happens that they don&rsquo;t like, and they smooth themselves out, turning this way and that &ndash; and not just towards the light, but also towards things they like, and turning away from things they dislike, and from people they dislike. But this happens in such a slow rhythm that the human eye does not register these things as movement. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Art has estranged and removed itself from nature so much in the last hundred years or more and has become so arrogant, dictatorially arrogant, that it is really high time for it to turn back. Artists must once again be able to think in terms of biology and plants and vegetation. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Organic thinking &ndash; a correspondence with organic growth &ndash; happens on many levels. That is not so simple; indeed, there are many ways to get closer to nature. One way is to copy it down, similarly to the way D&uuml;rer did; the other way is to perform actions on paper or in the painting which correspond to the growth of plants, that is, one tries to paint the way the plant grows. Something comes into being in and of itself. And that is true creation. As I said, one can also copy things down. By copying I mean not only the photographic copying down or artistic drawing, similarly to the way D&uuml;rer did it when he drew some grass or a rabbit. That is not photographic, there are a lot of other things in it, as well. By copying down I also mean when one copies down one&rsquo;s own dreams, one&rsquo;s inner world. The Surrealists, the Vienna School, that is, tries to copy dreams down to the minutest detail. One has a vision, one sees something with one&rsquo;s own eyes, and wants to eternalise it. That is copying down, too. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;The next step is to make something come about very slowly. That requires a lot of concentration, of course, and is only rarely successful. Very important is the love of eternity and the love of paint and material. The love of eternity &ndash; well, that brings me back to plants. The movements of plants are so slow that they are not seen by the naked eye, but only with the aid of time-lapse devices. If the artist paints quickly, the painting will only endure as long as the moment lasts in which he paints it. The viewer of the painting will only derive pleasure from it for a moment and then turn to other things. A moment-painting is like a flash photograph: taken in a moment, quickly made and quickly forgotten. The longer the period of time the painting embodies, the longer this painting will endure. One need only think of the &ldquo;Mona Lisa&rdquo; by Leonardo da Vinci. It is said of this painting that Leonardo worked on it for twenty, thirty years, that he began it as a portrait of a young girl, who then slowly became a mature woman. Maybe he even changed the model, or he portrayed himself; perhaps the features of several people are interwoven in this portrait &ndash; but in any case, a great deal of time was painted into it. The slower one paints, the more, the deeper one penetrates the secrets of paint. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;For painting is like prayer; painting is a religious activity. That cannot be done quickly. A great deal of devotion is needed to accomplish such a thing. A person who produces something offhandedly or thoughtlessly is himself the first to suffer. But by this I do not mean the attempts by Tachism to eliminate the intellect and let the laws of nature take their course, similar to the way Wols did, or Pollock, or in some ways Mathieu and Arnulf Rainer, too. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;All these people tried with really great conscientiousness to eliminate the intellect by blindfolding themselves, for example, by painting with their left hand or by taking drugs. That is an attempt to find oneself. It is also a drastic attempt to put oneself on an equal footing with nature, to get closer to nature.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Now I just mentioned several methods of getting closer to nature on various levels. Of course the Tachists failed to eliminate the intellect completely; only death can do that. Say you climb up a ladder with a bucket of paint and put a bullet through your head at the top and then fall down with the bucket of paint; then a genuine painting by nature will indeed result. That is, this splotch will really correspond to the laws of nature, and man will really have had little to do with it. But if a man climbs up the ladder and lets the paint fall from the top, a splotch will result, but it is something different after all. At any rate, that was a very dangerous activity, and we must be grateful to Tachism for having provided us with this wisdom, this milestone, this turning point in the history of art, without which we would be much poorer today.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Next is the love of paint, the love of the material. If you don&rsquo;t love the paint and material with which and on which you paint, the painting cannot amount to anything. It is totally impossible to use paint, paper, canvas and brush only as means to an end. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Paint is a living thing. Paint is something sacred &ndash; as are the brush, canvas and even paper, even the pencil, whatever &ndash; you have to be a kind of fetishist about all these things. You have to revere these things like gods. The pencil is a god, paint is a god, the brush is a god. Paint is like a piece of bread; it is something sacred. Just as you should not throw away bread or waste it, you shouldn&rsquo;t throw paint away or waste it, either.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;One doesn&rsquo;t paint arbitrarily, but purposively, for one knows very well that paint which isn&rsquo;t right, paint that has to be removed, paint that has to be thrown away, is a sin. By not throwing paint away I mean first of all that you don&rsquo;t throw paint in the garbage, partly used or even used-up tubes of paint, that is. Secondly, that you also shouldn&rsquo;t regard the canvas as a dustbin you can throw your paint away on, thinking it isn&rsquo;t worth anything anyway because it&rsquo;s just a study and will be thrown away: bad paints on bad paper, sketches on bad material which are thrown away afterwards and don&rsquo;t need to last anyway.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;The idea of a sketch is really something quite perverse. Making sketches for something which would be made later only emerged quite recently. I don&rsquo;t know whether it was two or three hundred years ago; in the history of mankind or even in the history of art, that is a tiny period. Either one made something pleasing to God, one created something, formed something, or one didn&rsquo;t. For that, no sketch or draft was needed beforehand. Whether you have a sketch or draft and then do it in larger or smaller format afterwards or do it again and better, in any case something is lost in the process, unless the sketch becomes a work in its own right, and the independent work one does afterwards is quite different from the sketch. That is also possible, of course.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;So don&rsquo;t throw paint away! Not in the dustbin, not on the paintings, and don&rsquo;t smear the walls without any aesthetic meaning or purpose, either, and don&rsquo;t wipe it on your smocks, on your own clothing or on cloths and rags! Paint should be treated as if it were your most valuable asset. Only as much paint should be taken out of the tube or prepared as will actually be used. I do it by measuring out the paint precisely &ndash; preferably a little less than too much. If I do prepare too much paint, I use the left-over paint for the next painting, for a second painting which is in progress, as it were. Often I paint for days with a single colour. I prepare blue often and paint everything that is blue. Not every colour is suited to everything. If one looks at the paintings of earlier centuries, there were colours which were used specifically for certain purposes, for providing certain hues, for setting off certain figures, for the sky or nature. Lapislazuli was only used for clothes, but not for the sky. Certain greens were only used as an underlayer for skin and flesh. It was impossible for a painter to take any kind of red and daub it here or there, the way it happens today, like a madman groping in the dark without knowing where he is going, smearing it here and there in the hope that somehow something unified will result. Nothing deep comes about this way, no nearness, no depth of vision and nothing tangible, nothing substantial. Although many colours are often used that way, the result is null and void. When I started painting I really had no money to buy paints and made do by just going to the Academy &ndash; I was not at the Academy at the time &ndash; and retrieving the paints thrown into the dustbins, whether in tubes or powder form, and then preparing them carefully and using them. A discarded tube of paint still had so much paint in it that I could paint with it for one or two years. One only need unfold the tube carefully at the rear and open it with a razor blade. Behind the tube&rsquo;s threading is a space where a lot of paint can be found. And inside the tube there is still so much paint left, too; you&rsquo;d be surprised.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;This throw-away business is a sin; something&rsquo;s got to change. The painter is not only a painter; he must also be an ecologist. The painter must be a revolutionary; he must stand at the vanguard of what will help human progress, and that can&rsquo;t happen in this day and age without nature and ecology. Without ecological awareness and without combatting the throw-away and consumer society, positive creativity is not possible.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;It is completely inappropriate and must by all means be condemned when a painter, who should be in the forefront of the fight for a better world, blindly imitates the throw-away society by being a paint consumer, as it were, the way a housewife is a consumer of detergents and other people are consumers of cars. The first step is for the painter to look on paint as his most precious asset. Dearer and more precious than gold. In earlier centuries, until almost a hundred years ago, the preparation of a painting, the prime ground, took longer than painting the picture itself. The wood the picture was painted on took a hundred years to grow. There were painting books which described that in detail, the painting books from Mount Athos, the painting books by the painter-monk Theophilus and by the Italian Cellini. There are also modern books which are very good, such as one by Doerner, whose German title translates as &ldquo;The Materials of the Artist and Their Use in Painting&rdquo;, and many others. In any case, the trees were split after drying and divided up with the tips pointing inward &ndash; the way a cake is cut. From the resulting segments the painting panels were very painstakingly split off, whittled and cut with utmost care, so that no veins in the wood were disturbed. It is thus no wonder that the panels have endured to the present day. Today, in contrast, they take wood, saw it up while paying no attention to the veins and structure of the wood, and then they are surprised that it doesn&rsquo;t last, that it cracks and twists, that it warps in all conceivable directions. The preparation of the ground also took up a lot of time, because the material also took decades to prepare. The lime for frescoes was a generation old, lying at least twenty-five years in the pit. It was inconceivable for lime to be slaked and immediately used or stirred with powder. The more fast-moving our civilisation becomes, the faster it will go to the dogs. Only he who thinks far into the future will survive long. I myself take a lot of time to produce the grounds for my paintings. Much more, I must say, than for the painting itself. First you have to make the frame, the &ldquo;chassis&rdquo;, that is. Now it is done by buying any old chassis, putting it together, stretching something over it, or by buying something which already has its canvas stretched over it and then painting away merrily. That is like today&rsquo;s clothes: nice and pretty on the outside and very ugly on the inside. Somebody should take the trouble to undress, take off his trousers, his shirt or take off skirt and blouse and then turn the trousers and shirt or skirt and blouse inside out and put them on again. Then you&rsquo;ll see how horrible that is. Take any painting, with which an artist wanted to achieve some ingenious feat, and turn the painting around and look at it from behind: it is an absolutely horrifying confusion. Then you see how bad the material is, how poorly the wood has been treated. The wood has not been stained, nor formed, nor whittled. Tatters are hanging down on the back. I always look at the reverse sides of paintings: only if they are beautiful at the back do I look at them from the front. It is interesting that all the paintings by the great masters, that is the Siena School, by D&uuml;rer, Breughel, are as beautiful from the back as from the front. The paintings can actually be looked at from behind and exhibited this way. The former director of the Kunsthistorisches Museum in Vienna, Vincenz Ludwig Oberhammer, exhibited the paintings in his care, the Breughels, D&uuml;rers and all the others from that approximate period, so that the visitors could walk around the paintings and look at them from the front and the back as well. The paintings were placed right out into the room, so that no detail of the reverse side was kept from view. The reverse side of the paintings is really more significant for the character of the painter than the front. That is why it is really important what the chassis looks like. The chassis must be visually and artistically and organically shaped, in its colour and form. The chassis must be a sculpture, in a way. And the canvas stretching over it must be perfect. If one hasn&rsquo;t woven it oneself, it must at least be stretched over it with care. And the ground should be perfect. What you consider perfect is left up to the individual.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Painting is a religious activity. Therefore one should be dressed as if for a sacred, very solemn occasion. Painting is a very solemn matter. That is why one should be dressed in tails, in one&rsquo;s best suit, not in a smock, for painting is not an activity where one gets dirty. Painting is an act of devotion, of harmony with oneself and the world, of self-discovery, of seeking and inspiration, of insight. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;It is now midnight in New Zealand. In Vienna it is two in the afternoon. And now I&rsquo;m going to bed; I&rsquo;ll continue tomorrow.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Today is May 13.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;The active pursuit of art should not just be self-therapy, that is, a therapy with whose help one cures and discovers oneself, which, as I have seen, is mainly the case with you. For those who are serious about it, it is mainly self-therapy, which means that many of you are lost and are trying and hoping to find yourselves with the aid of painting. Beyond this self-therapy, art should be more, by which I mean it should contribute something not just to the painter, but to the environment. So one must first find the bridge to oneself, after which one must find the bridge to nature and creation. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;That is the whole secret of art, a metaphor of art, finding the bridge to nature. The further away one is removed from nature, the more art fails. One of the most important secrets of nature is how it works, that is, how the cycle works, the cycle from life to death. That is why I used the symbol of the spiral, for example, which is a symbol of life and death, of expansion and concentration. Its origin from almost nothing and its vanishing in infinite space, the origin from infinite space and death at the smallest point. But I only mention this in passing.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Everyone must find his own way. The artist has the most important task to fulfill in our society, since all other fields are apparently a failure. By that I mean the gardeners are a failure; the doctors no longer know what they are doing; the architects are creating chaos, as we all know; the urban developers, the politicians are at their wits&rsquo; end; the priests are confused and embrace false dogmas. That is why the artist must ensure and contribute to the world&rsquo;s renewal. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Humanity needs to be shown a new way. But this new way cannot be ugly, which is what contemporary art has shown thus far, unfortunately. Contemporary art has thus far mainly shown what is negative; it was the mirror image of the negative consequences of our time, as it were. Art must not present merely the negative. Art must warn; that is its duty, but it must at the same time find a solution. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;By only warning and showing negative things and ruminating over the negative, by living in the vale of tears and shedding one&rsquo;s own as well, so to speak, you will not help humanity. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;People long for freedom, for beauty, for justice and for peace, within and without. That is why the artist cannot just be focused on his own therapy and try to keep himself out of the general misery. He must work for the others, and then he must show his way. The way must be one that can be taken, and it must be beautiful. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;That&rsquo;s why I am planning to have a way made from one entrance on the left side of the Academy to the classroom, with each of you helping to shape it, be it by designing a step, be it by embellishing part of the way with a mosaic or wood on the floor or wall, a way that can be walked on, a way that is beautiful, a way through nature, like through the forest, a way shaped so that one can tarry, where one can meditate. This Academy was built about a hundred years or more ago and is now a protected monument. Actually people shouldn&rsquo;t live and work in buildings which are protected monuments. Humans must be able to develop while at the same time respecting and preserving the old. That is no contradiction. It was possible with the old cathedrals, the old buildings, where the old part was preserved and added to or very slightly changed without destroying them. That could be done here in this Academy, too. It is of course depressing for someone who wants to work creatively to come into a building which is already finished. Nothing can be changed in its structure, when it is only natural to let a person change something about the structure he lives in, the house he lives in, on the wall, the masonry, the floor, the ceiling, the window, to widen or narrow the openings which serve as sources of light. So shape your work area! If this work area is like a mosque or a piece from the Garden of Eden, people will believe you are also capable of shaping the environment, and then they will let you tackle bigger things. But first you must begin at the micro level.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;The artist has the greatest task, so he must bear the greatest responsibility, as well. He must have the greatest intelligence, and he must be stronger. He must be a giant, in contrast to the other professions, which, as I have just said, have failed completely.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Next: the artist must be independent. He must be able to think critically and look for a positive solution in a creative way. It is totally wrong to devote oneself to the politics of the day; those are all transitory things. What is at stake today is the attitude of the world in general. We must conclude a peace treaty with nature. The artist is in a unique position to prepare this peace treaty with nature, because art is, after all, the bridge between man and nature. This is no longer a matter of petty quarrels among people, of religion or capitalism or communism. These are ridiculous disputes between people which distract attention from the core issue, namely our peace with nature, which must be restored at all costs if we are to survive.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Next: art cannot constantly depict our vale of tears. Art must find a way to a more beautiful world. The fine arts &ndash; the beaux arts &ndash; must be beautiful or else they cannot exist. If the fine arts are ugly, they are not art. Fine art can indeed and must be critical and severe and show blood, but it must at the same time have substance and show a way which everyone can follow. A painting must be something like a cathedral, like a chapel one can repair to in order to find comfort and consolation, but also a way out. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;A way for everyone must be one that can be taken, and only the ways one likes to follow are such ways. People don&rsquo;t like to walk down an ugly path. Only when one has no choice does one walk through industrial areas, for example, where everything is straight and where it stinks. That is an ugly way. People like to walk on a winding path lined by trees, not a monoculture, but a variety of natural growth. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;So don&rsquo;t be copycats, don&rsquo;t run after some ideas or games which others have come up with; don&rsquo;t become devotees of something which already exists, but create something yourselves from inside. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;You can only do that if you lay bare your origins. Then you can go on from there. The artist must be strong and self-confident, he must be beautiful, and he must make an impression. That must express itself in your clothing and in your surroundings, which you must shape, and in your works, too. When you go out on the street, people must already realise that a light, a radiance emanates from you. If that is the case, this strength will also find its way into the painting, to the flat surface you are painting on. That will happen entirely of its own accord, you don&rsquo;t need to worry about it or torture yourself. Then a mighty stream will flow directly onto the canvas, so to speak, which can&rsquo;t be held back.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Another thing to consider is that you should paint flat, flat on the table, and not upright on easels. That is also a preparation for the peace treaty with nature. Everything horizontal belongs to nature. Nature can only be understood if confronted horizontally. The vertical is the domain of man. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;So everything horizontal under the open sky belongs to nature. We have misappropriated territories from nature which we must give back to her. Every individual can begin doing this by laying the painting horizontally on the table and trying to create something similar to nature&rsquo;s horizontalness, a painting, that is, which has no top and no bottom, but which is looked at from above. That is, as it were, a sacrificial offering to the sky, to nature, to the universe. Paintings which are upright, easel paintings, are nothing more than mirror images of man&rsquo;s ineptness. Man wants to recognise himself in the painting. Easel paintings are more or less poorly painted mirrors. The easel painting has only existed in human history for a short time. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Before that there was no such thing as paintings at all; there wasn&rsquo;t any art, either, for if one is in union and harmony with nature and the environment, one has no need for art, one is art, one is nature, one is in everything one does, in thinking and actions and deeds, in unison with the eternal laws of the cosmos, and one needs no substitutes, one of which is, unfortunately, art.&lt;/p&gt;',
text_contents_en-'&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Dear Friends,&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Today is May 12, 1982. I am in New Zealand.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;It is already pretty cold here by now, May being about what November is in Europe. It is now a quarter past ten in the &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;evening; in Vienna it is a quarter past noon. Here everything is the other way round. Here you see the Southern Cross, warmth comes from the north, cold from the south. You are surely wondering why I am staying away so long, but the main reason for it is that I don&rsquo;t think one can learn anything at the Academy; only the weak go to the Academy; only the weak think they can study art, that they can learn art. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Either you have it in you like an inspiration which suddenly comes, or you look and look and usually don&rsquo;t find it. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Either you have the gifts you have been endowed with already as a child, from birth, or you don&rsquo;t. But if you have these gifts, you run the greatest risk at the Academy or at any school or any association with other people of losing the most precious of all the assets in your possession: of losing your own self. But if you have not found your own self or have lost it and want to recover it, the Academy is the worst possible place. For there you are exposed to influences which do not fit you, and there is a very great danger of adopting something which you then imagine to be yourself, as it were, that you recognise yourself in the knowledge and actions of other people, that you identify with something that is not yourself, with something you would like to be but aren&rsquo;t and then suffer from it all your life. It is as if you had put on a false skin or donned clothes which don&rsquo;t fit and now wanted to grow into these clothes, so to speak.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;That is why I told you at the outset, as you&rsquo;ll recall, to bring in your own childhood drawings. Everyone should begin at the point where he was still himself, before he was inundated, before he was alienated, by his parental home, by the system of upbringing, by school, by the customary ways of our civilisation. For one can only continue building from the ground up. That is the only solid, secure, unshakeable basis, one&rsquo;s own origins. It is irrelevant what these childhood drawings look like. One can only build on this basis; otherwise it is a castle in the air, a house of cards which will collapse. You can&rsquo;t build by putting heavy bricks on flimsy matchboxes.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Since you of course don&rsquo;t want to go home &ndash; just as I experienced once before, when I taught briefly in Hamburg &ndash; I want each of you to remember who you are by having your own berth, your own world, your own house in the Master School, where you come into as little contact as possible with what is around you. You should then regard this berth, this world, as your origin, around which everything will be built. That is the centre of activity, so to speak. This berth should be closed off from external influences, from influences of your neighbours and in particular from my own influence. For nothing is more dangerous than to try to subject yourself to my influence, to the influence of the master, in the parlance of the Master School. That is extremely dangerous. You must go your own way, and I must stress once again: if anyone paints similarly to the way I do, or even vaguely approaches it, he must leave; then there is just no point to it. For me it is embarrassing, and for the person who does it, it is a death sentence.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;The next question is why I put trees in the classrooms. It is perfectly clear: art and nature have a lot to do with one another. Art is the bridge between man and nature. Art is not the bridge between people. What art is, must be worked out by everyone for himself in a dialogue with nature. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Man cannot be creative the way creation was, the way God creates trees, nature, plants, brings forth flowers, brings forth worlds which then go on existing of their own accord and, thanks to an incredible diversity, have a raison d&rsquo;&ecirc;tre of their own and form an interlinking clockwork: man cannot do that, no matter how much he exerts his intellect. On the contrary, the harder he exerts his intellect, the less progress is made. Man only makes progress when he lets other things work, apart from his intellect. His intellect should only be a cause for him to control himself, but not to be haughty towards nature. Man achieves nothing by force; the artist, in particular, achieves nothing by force. The era when the artist was a dictator is coming to a close. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;The artist can only be a mediator between man and nature if he has special antennae, if he is a medium, as it were, a receiving station, if he can listen, if he can be a tool for this certain something which comes from somewhere else. If he can throw open gates to another, better, more beautiful world, to a more genuine world. And that is a parallel world. That is a world which we sometimes get hold of in dreams. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Of course it would be completely wrong, in turn, to take drugs to reach that world. You don&rsquo;t reach that world with drugs, and if you did, it wouldn&rsquo;t do you any good because you would destroy yourself in the process. You can only enter that world with the full consciousness of your spiritual powers and as a go-between, that is to say as a very gentle, careful listener. If one has observed and listened well, with humility, so to speak, then it is possible to know that world and impart that fantastic world which is inside one and also all around one, and when one gets hold of that world, one is overwhelmed by a feeling of great happiness. Then one feels not only satisfied with oneself &ndash; for painting is not only a self-healing activity, after all &ndash; but should in addition also be able to have an effect on other people. But if one wants to arrive at greater truth in larger dimensions, one which also concerns other people, one has to listen more deeply, of course, and set one&rsquo;s own ego aside, put one&rsquo;s own intellect even further away &ndash; but not criticism of oneself. Dal&iacute; said a very good thing: &ldquo;la m&eacute;thode paranoya critique&rdquo;, that is, one should be abnormal, but at the same time have a self-critical attitude towards this abnormality. This seeming contradiction is very important in painting, however. On the one hand one should and must let oneself go, drift and flow, as it were, the way a cloud drifts along and a river flows, and the way the grass grows and a flower opens up; on the other hand one must be critical of oneself.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;As art is a bridge between man and nature, it is of utmost importance that one compares what one does with the achievements, with the creativity of nature. If what one does oneself can withstand a comparison with nature, comparison with a leaf, with a tree, then one can be very content. The growth of plants is an amazing thing. The plants yawn and stretch, wrinkle their leaves if something happens that they don&rsquo;t like, and they smooth themselves out, turning this way and that &ndash; and not just towards the light, but also towards things they like, and turning away from things they dislike, and from people they dislike. But this happens in such a slow rhythm that the human eye does not register these things as movement. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Art has estranged and removed itself from nature so much in the last hundred years or more and has become so arrogant, dictatorially arrogant, that it is really high time for it to turn back. Artists must once again be able to think in terms of biology and plants and vegetation. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Organic thinking &ndash; a correspondence with organic growth &ndash; happens on many levels. That is not so simple; indeed, there are many ways to get closer to nature. One way is to copy it down, similarly to the way D&uuml;rer did; the other way is to perform actions on paper or in the painting which correspond to the growth of plants, that is, one tries to paint the way the plant grows. Something comes into being in and of itself. And that is true creation. As I said, one can also copy things down. By copying I mean not only the photographic copying down or artistic drawing, similarly to the way D&uuml;rer did it when he drew some grass or a rabbit. That is not photographic, there are a lot of other things in it, as well. By copying down I also mean when one copies down one&rsquo;s own dreams, one&rsquo;s inner world. The Surrealists, the Vienna School, that is, tries to copy dreams down to the minutest detail. One has a vision, one sees something with one&rsquo;s own eyes, and wants to eternalise it. That is copying down, too. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;The next step is to make something come about very slowly. That requires a lot of concentration, of course, and is only rarely successful. Very important is the love of eternity and the love of paint and material. The love of eternity &ndash; well, that brings me back to plants. The movements of plants are so slow that they are not seen by the naked eye, but only with the aid of time-lapse devices. If the artist paints quickly, the painting will only endure as long as the moment lasts in which he paints it. The viewer of the painting will only derive pleasure from it for a moment and then turn to other things. A moment-painting is like a flash photograph: taken in a moment, quickly made and quickly forgotten. The longer the period of time the painting embodies, the longer this painting will endure. One need only think of the &ldquo;Mona Lisa&rdquo; by Leonardo da Vinci. It is said of this painting that Leonardo worked on it for twenty, thirty years, that he began it as a portrait of a young girl, who then slowly became a mature woman. Maybe he even changed the model, or he portrayed himself; perhaps the features of several people are interwoven in this portrait &ndash; but in any case, a great deal of time was painted into it. The slower one paints, the more, the deeper one penetrates the secrets of paint. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;For painting is like prayer; painting is a religious activity. That cannot be done quickly. A great deal of devotion is needed to accomplish such a thing. A person who produces something offhandedly or thoughtlessly is himself the first to suffer. But by this I do not mean the attempts by Tachism to eliminate the intellect and let the laws of nature take their course, similar to the way Wols did, or Pollock, or in some ways Mathieu and Arnulf Rainer, too. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;All these people tried with really great conscientiousness to eliminate the intellect by blindfolding themselves, for example, by painting with their left hand or by taking drugs. That is an attempt to find oneself. It is also a drastic attempt to put oneself on an equal footing with nature, to get closer to nature.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Now I just mentioned several methods of getting closer to nature on various levels. Of course the Tachists failed to eliminate the intellect completely; only death can do that. Say you climb up a ladder with a bucket of paint and put a bullet through your head at the top and then fall down with the bucket of paint; then a genuine painting by nature will indeed result. That is, this splotch will really correspond to the laws of nature, and man will really have had little to do with it. But if a man climbs up the ladder and lets the paint fall from the top, a splotch will result, but it is something different after all. At any rate, that was a very dangerous activity, and we must be grateful to Tachism for having provided us with this wisdom, this milestone, this turning point in the history of art, without which we would be much poorer today.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Next is the love of paint, the love of the material. If you don&rsquo;t love the paint and material with which and on which you paint, the painting cannot amount to anything. It is totally impossible to use paint, paper, canvas and brush only as means to an end. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Paint is a living thing. Paint is something sacred &ndash; as are the brush, canvas and even paper, even the pencil, whatever &ndash; you have to be a kind of fetishist about all these things. You have to revere these things like gods. The pencil is a god, paint is a god, the brush is a god. Paint is like a piece of bread; it is something sacred. Just as you should not throw away bread or waste it, you shouldn&rsquo;t throw paint away or waste it, either.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;One doesn&rsquo;t paint arbitrarily, but purposively, for one knows very well that paint which isn&rsquo;t right, paint that has to be removed, paint that has to be thrown away, is a sin. By not throwing paint away I mean first of all that you don&rsquo;t throw paint in the garbage, partly used or even used-up tubes of paint, that is. Secondly, that you also shouldn&rsquo;t regard the canvas as a dustbin you can throw your paint away on, thinking it isn&rsquo;t worth anything anyway because it&rsquo;s just a study and will be thrown away: bad paints on bad paper, sketches on bad material which are thrown away afterwards and don&rsquo;t need to last anyway.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;The idea of a sketch is really something quite perverse. Making sketches for something which would be made later only emerged quite recently. I don&rsquo;t know whether it was two or three hundred years ago; in the history of mankind or even in the history of art, that is a tiny period. Either one made something pleasing to God, one created something, formed something, or one didn&rsquo;t. For that, no sketch or draft was needed beforehand. Whether you have a sketch or draft and then do it in larger or smaller format afterwards or do it again and better, in any case something is lost in the process, unless the sketch becomes a work in its own right, and the independent work one does afterwards is quite different from the sketch. That is also possible, of course.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;So don&rsquo;t throw paint away! Not in the dustbin, not on the paintings, and don&rsquo;t smear the walls without any aesthetic meaning or purpose, either, and don&rsquo;t wipe it on your smocks, on your own clothing or on cloths and rags! Paint should be treated as if it were your most valuable asset. Only as much paint should be taken out of the tube or prepared as will actually be used. I do it by measuring out the paint precisely &ndash; preferably a little less than too much. If I do prepare too much paint, I use the left-over paint for the next painting, for a second painting which is in progress, as it were. Often I paint for days with a single colour. I prepare blue often and paint everything that is blue. Not every colour is suited to everything. If one looks at the paintings of earlier centuries, there were colours which were used specifically for certain purposes, for providing certain hues, for setting off certain figures, for the sky or nature. Lapislazuli was only used for clothes, but not for the sky. Certain greens were only used as an underlayer for skin and flesh. It was impossible for a painter to take any kind of red and daub it here or there, the way it happens today, like a madman groping in the dark without knowing where he is going, smearing it here and there in the hope that somehow something unified will result. Nothing deep comes about this way, no nearness, no depth of vision and nothing tangible, nothing substantial. Although many colours are often used that way, the result is null and void. When I started painting I really had no money to buy paints and made do by just going to the Academy &ndash; I was not at the Academy at the time &ndash; and retrieving the paints thrown into the dustbins, whether in tubes or powder form, and then preparing them carefully and using them. A discarded tube of paint still had so much paint in it that I could paint with it for one or two years. One only need unfold the tube carefully at the rear and open it with a razor blade. Behind the tube&rsquo;s threading is a space where a lot of paint can be found. And inside the tube there is still so much paint left, too; you&rsquo;d be surprised.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;This throw-away business is a sin; something&rsquo;s got to change. The painter is not only a painter; he must also be an ecologist. The painter must be a revolutionary; he must stand at the vanguard of what will help human progress, and that can&rsquo;t happen in this day and age without nature and ecology. Without ecological awareness and without combatting the throw-away and consumer society, positive creativity is not possible.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;It is completely inappropriate and must by all means be condemned when a painter, who should be in the forefront of the fight for a better world, blindly imitates the throw-away society by being a paint consumer, as it were, the way a housewife is a consumer of detergents and other people are consumers of cars. The first step is for the painter to look on paint as his most precious asset. Dearer and more precious than gold. In earlier centuries, until almost a hundred years ago, the preparation of a painting, the prime ground, took longer than painting the picture itself. The wood the picture was painted on took a hundred years to grow. There were painting books which described that in detail, the painting books from Mount Athos, the painting books by the painter-monk Theophilus and by the Italian Cellini. There are also modern books which are very good, such as one by Doerner, whose German title translates as &ldquo;The Materials of the Artist and Their Use in Painting&rdquo;, and many others. In any case, the trees were split after drying and divided up with the tips pointing inward &ndash; the way a cake is cut. From the resulting segments the painting panels were very painstakingly split off, whittled and cut with utmost care, so that no veins in the wood were disturbed. It is thus no wonder that the panels have endured to the present day. Today, in contrast, they take wood, saw it up while paying no attention to the veins and structure of the wood, and then they are surprised that it doesn&rsquo;t last, that it cracks and twists, that it warps in all conceivable directions. The preparation of the ground also took up a lot of time, because the material also took decades to prepare. The lime for frescoes was a generation old, lying at least twenty-five years in the pit. It was inconceivable for lime to be slaked and immediately used or stirred with powder. The more fast-moving our civilisation becomes, the faster it will go to the dogs. Only he who thinks far into the future will survive long. I myself take a lot of time to produce the grounds for my paintings. Much more, I must say, than for the painting itself. First you have to make the frame, the &ldquo;chassis&rdquo;, that is. Now it is done by buying any old chassis, putting it together, stretching something over it, or by buying something which already has its canvas stretched over it and then painting away merrily. That is like today&rsquo;s clothes: nice and pretty on the outside and very ugly on the inside. Somebody should take the trouble to undress, take off his trousers, his shirt or take off skirt and blouse and then turn the trousers and shirt or skirt and blouse inside out and put them on again. Then you&rsquo;ll see how horrible that is. Take any painting, with which an artist wanted to achieve some ingenious feat, and turn the painting around and look at it from behind: it is an absolutely horrifying confusion. Then you see how bad the material is, how poorly the wood has been treated. The wood has not been stained, nor formed, nor whittled. Tatters are hanging down on the back. I always look at the reverse sides of paintings: only if they are beautiful at the back do I look at them from the front. It is interesting that all the paintings by the great masters, that is the Siena School, by D&uuml;rer, Breughel, are as beautiful from the back as from the front. The paintings can actually be looked at from behind and exhibited this way. The former director of the Kunsthistorisches Museum in Vienna, Vincenz Ludwig Oberhammer, exhibited the paintings in his care, the Breughels, D&uuml;rers and all the others from that approximate period, so that the visitors could walk around the paintings and look at them from the front and the back as well. The paintings were placed right out into the room, so that no detail of the reverse side was kept from view. The reverse side of the paintings is really more significant for the character of the painter than the front. That is why it is really important what the chassis looks like. The chassis must be visually and artistically and organically shaped, in its colour and form. The chassis must be a sculpture, in a way. And the canvas stretching over it must be perfect. If one hasn&rsquo;t woven it oneself, it must at least be stretched over it with care. And the ground should be perfect. What you consider perfect is left up to the individual.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Painting is a religious activity. Therefore one should be dressed as if for a sacred, very solemn occasion. Painting is a very solemn matter. That is why one should be dressed in tails, in one&rsquo;s best suit, not in a smock, for painting is not an activity where one gets dirty. Painting is an act of devotion, of harmony with oneself and the world, of self-discovery, of seeking and inspiration, of insight. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;It is now midnight in New Zealand. In Vienna it is two in the afternoon. And now I&rsquo;m going to bed; I&rsquo;ll continue tomorrow.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Today is May 13.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;The active pursuit of art should not just be self-therapy, that is, a therapy with whose help one cures and discovers oneself, which, as I have seen, is mainly the case with you. For those who are serious about it, it is mainly self-therapy, which means that many of you are lost and are trying and hoping to find yourselves with the aid of painting. Beyond this self-therapy, art should be more, by which I mean it should contribute something not just to the painter, but to the environment. So one must first find the bridge to oneself, after which one must find the bridge to nature and creation. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;That is the whole secret of art, a metaphor of art, finding the bridge to nature. The further away one is removed from nature, the more art fails. One of the most important secrets of nature is how it works, that is, how the cycle works, the cycle from life to death. That is why I used the symbol of the spiral, for example, which is a symbol of life and death, of expansion and concentration. Its origin from almost nothing and its vanishing in infinite space, the origin from infinite space and death at the smallest point. But I only mention this in passing.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Everyone must find his own way. The artist has the most important task to fulfill in our society, since all other fields are apparently a failure. By that I mean the gardeners are a failure; the doctors no longer know what they are doing; the architects are creating chaos, as we all know; the urban developers, the politicians are at their wits&rsquo; end; the priests are confused and embrace false dogmas. That is why the artist must ensure and contribute to the world&rsquo;s renewal. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Humanity needs to be shown a new way. But this new way cannot be ugly, which is what contemporary art has shown thus far, unfortunately. Contemporary art has thus far mainly shown what is negative; it was the mirror image of the negative consequences of our time, as it were. Art must not present merely the negative. Art must warn; that is its duty, but it must at the same time find a solution. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;By only warning and showing negative things and ruminating over the negative, by living in the vale of tears and shedding one&rsquo;s own as well, so to speak, you will not help humanity. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;People long for freedom, for beauty, for justice and for peace, within and without. That is why the artist cannot just be focused on his own therapy and try to keep himself out of the general misery. He must work for the others, and then he must show his way. The way must be one that can be taken, and it must be beautiful. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;That&rsquo;s why I am planning to have a way made from one entrance on the left side of the Academy to the classroom, with each of you helping to shape it, be it by designing a step, be it by embellishing part of the way with a mosaic or wood on the floor or wall, a way that can be walked on, a way that is beautiful, a way through nature, like through the forest, a way shaped so that one can tarry, where one can meditate. This Academy was built about a hundred years or more ago and is now a protected monument. Actually people shouldn&rsquo;t live and work in buildings which are protected monuments. Humans must be able to develop while at the same time respecting and preserving the old. That is no contradiction. It was possible with the old cathedrals, the old buildings, where the old part was preserved and added to or very slightly changed without destroying them. That could be done here in this Academy, too. It is of course depressing for someone who wants to work creatively to come into a building which is already finished. Nothing can be changed in its structure, when it is only natural to let a person change something about the structure he lives in, the house he lives in, on the wall, the masonry, the floor, the ceiling, the window, to widen or narrow the openings which serve as sources of light. So shape your work area! If this work area is like a mosque or a piece from the Garden of Eden, people will believe you are also capable of shaping the environment, and then they will let you tackle bigger things. But first you must begin at the micro level.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;The artist has the greatest task, so he must bear the greatest responsibility, as well. He must have the greatest intelligence, and he must be stronger. He must be a giant, in contrast to the other professions, which, as I have just said, have failed completely.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Next: the artist must be independent. He must be able to think critically and look for a positive solution in a creative way. It is totally wrong to devote oneself to the politics of the day; those are all transitory things. What is at stake today is the attitude of the world in general. We must conclude a peace treaty with nature. The artist is in a unique position to prepare this peace treaty with nature, because art is, after all, the bridge between man and nature. This is no longer a matter of petty quarrels among people, of religion or capitalism or communism. These are ridiculous disputes between people which distract attention from the core issue, namely our peace with nature, which must be restored at all costs if we are to survive.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Next: art cannot constantly depict our vale of tears. Art must find a way to a more beautiful world. The fine arts &ndash; the beaux arts &ndash; must be beautiful or else they cannot exist. If the fine arts are ugly, they are not art. Fine art can indeed and must be critical and severe and show blood, but it must at the same time have substance and show a way which everyone can follow. A painting must be something like a cathedral, like a chapel one can repair to in order to find comfort and consolation, but also a way out. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;A way for everyone must be one that can be taken, and only the ways one likes to follow are such ways. People don&rsquo;t like to walk down an ugly path. Only when one has no choice does one walk through industrial areas, for example, where everything is straight and where it stinks. That is an ugly way. People like to walk on a winding path lined by trees, not a monoculture, but a variety of natural growth. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;So don&rsquo;t be copycats, don&rsquo;t run after some ideas or games which others have come up with; don&rsquo;t become devotees of something which already exists, but create something yourselves from inside. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;You can only do that if you lay bare your origins. Then you can go on from there. The artist must be strong and self-confident, he must be beautiful, and he must make an impression. That must express itself in your clothing and in your surroundings, which you must shape, and in your works, too. When you go out on the street, people must already realise that a light, a radiance emanates from you. If that is the case, this strength will also find its way into the painting, to the flat surface you are painting on. That will happen entirely of its own accord, you don&rsquo;t need to worry about it or torture yourself. Then a mighty stream will flow directly onto the canvas, so to speak, which can&rsquo;t be held back.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Another thing to consider is that you should paint flat, flat on the table, and not upright on easels. That is also a preparation for the peace treaty with nature. Everything horizontal belongs to nature. Nature can only be understood if confronted horizontally. The vertical is the domain of man. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;So everything horizontal under the open sky belongs to nature. We have misappropriated territories from nature which we must give back to her. Every individual can begin doing this by laying the painting horizontally on the table and trying to create something similar to nature&rsquo;s horizontalness, a painting, that is, which has no top and no bottom, but which is looked at from above. That is, as it were, a sacrificial offering to the sky, to nature, to the universe. Paintings which are upright, easel paintings, are nothing more than mirror images of man&rsquo;s ineptness. Man wants to recognise himself in the painting. Easel paintings are more or less poorly painted mirrors. The easel painting has only existed in human history for a short time. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Before that there was no such thing as paintings at all; there wasn&rsquo;t any art, either, for if one is in union and harmony with nature and the environment, one has no need for art, one is art, one is nature, one is in everything one does, in thinking and actions and deeds, in unison with the eternal laws of the cosmos, and one needs no substitutes, one of which is, unfortunately, art.&lt;/p&gt;',
text_contents_ge-'&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Liebe Freunde,&nbsp;&nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;heute ist der 12. Mai 1982. Ich bin in Neuseeland.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Es ist jetzt schon ziemlich kalt hier, denn Mai ist ungef&auml;hr, was in Europa November ist. Es ist jetzt 10 Uhr 15 abends, in Wien ist es eine Viertelstunde nach Mittag. Es ist hier alles verkehrt. Hier sieht man das Kreuz des S&uuml;dens, die W&auml;rme kommt aus dem Norden, die K&auml;lte kommt aus dem S&uuml;den. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Ihr werdet Euch sicher wundern, warum ich so lange weg bin, aber das hat haupts&auml;chlich den Grund darin, da&szlig; ich nicht glaube, da&szlig; man an der Akademie etwas lernen kann. Nur die Schwachen gehen auf die Akademie, nur die Schwachen glauben, da&szlig; sie Kunst studieren k&ouml;nnen, da&szlig; sie Kunst lernen k&ouml;nnen.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Entweder hat man das in sich wie eine Erleuchtung, die einem pl&ouml;tzlich kommt, oder man sucht und sucht und sucht und findet es meistens nicht. Entweder besitzt man die Gaben, die man bekommen hat, schon als Kind, seit seiner Geburt, oder man hat sie nicht. Hat man aber diese Gaben, so l&auml;uft man die gr&ouml;&szlig;te Gefahr in der Akademie oder in jeder Schule oder in jedem Zusammensein mit anderen Menschen, dieses kostbarste Gut, das man besitzt, n&auml;mlich sein eigenes ICH zu verlieren.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Hat man aber sein eigenes ICH nicht gefunden oder es verloren und will es wiederfinden, so ist die Akademie der allerschlechteste Ort. Denn dort ist man Einfl&uuml;ssen ausgesetzt, die einem nicht entsprechen und es besteht die gr&ouml;&szlig;te Gefahr, da&szlig; man irgendetwas adoptiert und dann sozusagen als sein Selbst erkennt, da&szlig; man sich in dem Wissen und dem Tun anderer Leute erkennt, da&szlig; man sich identifiziert mit etwas, das man selber nicht ist, mit etwas, das man gerne sein m&ouml;chte, aber nicht ist, und dann leidet man sein ganzes Leben lang darunter. Das ist so, wie wenn man sich eine falsche Haut umgebunden hat oder wenn man Kleider anzieht, die einem nicht passen, und man sozusagen in diese Kleider hineinwachsen will.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Deswegen habe ich zu Beginn, wie Ihr Euch erinnert, gesagt, jeder soll doch seine eigenen Kinderzeichnungen herbringen. Jeder soll dort beginnen, wo er noch er selbst war, bevor er zugesch&uuml;ttet wurde, bevor er entfremdet wurde, durch das Elternhaus, durch das Erziehungssystem, durch die Schule, durch die Gepflogenheiten unserer Zivilisation. Denn nur vom Ursprung aus kann man aufbauen. Das ist die einzige feste, sichere, unverr&uuml;ckbare Basis, der eigene Ursprung. Ganz gleich, wie diese Kinderzeichnungen ausgesehen haben. Nur auf diese Basis kann man aufbauen, ansonsten ist es ein Luftschlo&szlig;, ein Kartenhaus, das zusammenbricht. Man kann nicht schwere Ziegel auf verkr&uuml;mmte Streichholzschachteln aufbauen.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Da Ihr nat&uuml;rlich nicht nach Hause gehen wollt - so wie ich das schon einmal erfahren habe, als ich kurz in Hamburg t&auml;tig war -, so m&ouml;chte ich, da&szlig; jeder sich auf sich selbst besinnt, und zwar so, da&szlig; jeder seine eigene Koje, seine eigene Welt, sein eigenes Haus hat in der Meisterschule, wo er eigentlich so wenig wie m&ouml;glich in Kontakt kommt mit dem, was um ihn herum ist. Dann m&ouml;ge er diese Koje, diese Welt betrachten als den Ursprung, um den alles gebaut wird. Das ist sozusagen das Zentrum des Wirkens. Diese Koje soll abgeschlossen sein gegen &auml;u&szlig;ere Einfl&uuml;sse, gegen Einfl&uuml;sse des Nachbarn und insbesondere gegen meinen eigenen Einflu&szlig;. Denn nichts ist gef&auml;hrlicher, als wenn man versucht, meinem Einflu&szlig; zu unterliegen, dem Einflu&szlig; des Meisters, wie das so sch&ouml;n hei&szlig;t in der Meisterschule. Das ist &auml;u&szlig;erst gef&auml;hrlich. Ihr m&uuml;&szlig;t den eigenen Weg gehen, und ich mu&szlig; nochmals betonen: Wenn irgend jemand so &auml;hnlich malt, &uuml;berhaupt in die N&auml;he dessen kommt, wie ich male, dann mu&szlig; er gehen, dann hat das keinen Zweck. F&uuml;r mich ist das peinlich und f&uuml;r den, der das macht, ist es ein Todesurteil.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Das n&auml;chste ist: Warum ich B&auml;ume in die Klassen hineingestellt habe? Es ist ganz klar: Kunst und Natur haben sehr viel miteinander zu tun. Kunst ist die Br&uuml;cke zwischen Mensch und Natur. Kunst ist nicht die Br&uuml;cke zwischen den Menschen. Was Kunst ist, mu&szlig; sich jeder selbst aushandeln im Zwiegespr&auml;ch mit der Natur. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Der Mensch kann nicht kreativ sein, so wie die Sch&ouml;pfung kreativ war, d.h. so wie Gott B&auml;ume schafft, Natur schafft, Pflanzen schafft, Blumen hervorbringt, Welten hervorbringt, die dann durch sich selbst weiter existieren und aufgrund einer unglaublichen Mannigfaltigkeit ihre Daseinsberechtigung haben, ein R&auml;derwerk bilden, das ineinandergreift: Das kann der Mensch nicht, so sehr er sich auch intellektuell strapaziert. Im Gegenteil, je mehr er sich intellektuell strapaziert, um so weniger kommt er vorw&auml;rts. Der Mensch kommt nur dann vorw&auml;rts, wenn er neben seinem Intellekt andere Dinge wirken l&auml;&szlig;t. Intellekt soll ihn nur zur Selbstbeherrschung veranlassen, aber nicht zu Hochm&uuml;tigkeit gegen&uuml;ber der Natur. Mit Gewalt erreicht der Mensch nichts, mit Gewalt erreicht insbesondere der K&uuml;nstler nichts. Das Zeitalter, in dem der K&uuml;nstler Diktator war, geht dem Ende zu. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Der K&uuml;nstler kann nur dann Mittler sein zwischen Mensch und Natur, wenn er besondere Antennen hat, wenn er sozusagen ein Medium ist und eine Empfangsstation, wenn er horchen kann, wenn er Werkzeug sein kann, f&uuml;r dieses gewisse Etwas, das von woanders herkommt. Wenn er Tore aufsto&szlig;en kann in eine andere, bessere, sch&ouml;nere Welt, in eine echtere Welt. Und das ist eine Parallelwelt. Das ist eine Welt, die wir manchmal im Traum zu fassen bekommen.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Es w&auml;re nat&uuml;rlich wiederum v&ouml;llig falsch, Drogen zu nehmen, um in diese Welt zu gelangen. In diese Welt gelangt man nicht mit Drogen, und wenn, dann hat man nichts davon, man geht dabei selbst zugrunde. In diese Welt kann man nur im vollen Bewu&szlig;tsein seiner Geisteskraft eintreten und als Mittler, und zwar als sehr sanfter, behutsamer Lauscher. Wenn man gut gesehen und gelauscht hat, in Demut sozusagen, dann ist es m&ouml;glich, diese Welt zu kennen und diese phantastische Welt zu vermitteln, die in einem selbst ist und die auch um einem herum ist, und wenn man diese Welt zu fassen bekommt, dann &uuml;berkommt einen ein gro&szlig;es Gl&uuml;cksgef&uuml;hl. Dann kann man nicht nur sich selbst befriedigen - denn Malen ist ja nicht nur eine selbstheilende T&auml;tigkeit - sondern soll dar&uuml;ber hinaus auch auf andere Menschen Wirkung haben k&ouml;nnen. Wenn man aber gr&ouml;&szlig;ere Wahrheit in gr&ouml;&szlig;eren Dimensionen erreichen will, die auch andere Menschen betrifft, so mu&szlig; man nat&uuml;rlich tiefer horchen und sein eigenes Ich weiter beiseite schieben, seinen eigenen Intellekt noch weiter zur Seite schieben - aber nicht die Kritik an sich selbst. Dali hat etwas sehr Sch&ouml;nes gesagt, &bdquo;la m&eacute;thode paranoya critique&ldquo;, d.h. also, man soll abnormal sein, aber dieser Abnormalit&auml;t gleichzeitig selbstkritisch gegen&uuml;berstehen. Dieser scheinbare Widerspruch ist aber sehr wichtig in der Malerei. Auf der einen Seite soll man und mu&szlig; man sich gehen lassen, sozusagen fliegen und flie&szlig;en, wie die Wolke zieht und wie der Flu&szlig; flie&szlig;t und wie das Gras w&auml;chst und die Blume sich entfaltet, auf der anderen Seite mu&szlig; man sich selbst kritisch gegen&uuml;ber stehen.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Da die Kunst eine Br&uuml;cke ist zwischen Mensch und Natur, so ist es von allergr&ouml;&szlig;ter Bedeutung, da&szlig; man das, was man tut, mit den Errungenschaften, mit der Sch&ouml;pfung der Natur vergleicht.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;&nbsp;Wenn das, was man selbst tut, einen Vergleich mit der Natur aush&auml;lt, den Vergleich mit einem Blatt, mit einem Baum, dann kann man schon sehr zufrieden sein. Das Wachstum der Pflanzen ist etwas Ungeheures. Die Pflanzen g&auml;hnen und strecken sich, runzeln ihre Bl&auml;tter, wenn ihnen etwas nicht pa&szlig;t, und gl&auml;tten sich, drehen sich hierhin und dorthin - und zwar nicht nur nach dem Licht, sondern auch nach Dingen, die sie m&ouml;gen, und wenden sich ab von Dingen, die sie nicht m&ouml;gen, auch von Menschen, die sie nicht m&ouml;gen. Aber das geschieht in einem derartig langsamen Rhythmus, da&szlig; das menschliche Auge diese Dinge nicht als Bewegung erkennt. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Die Kunst hat in den letzten hundert oder mehr Jahren sich derartig von der Natur entfremdet und entfernt und ist derartig &uuml;berheblich geworden, diktatorisch &uuml;berheblich, da&szlig; es wirklich an der Zeit ist f&uuml;r eine Umkehr. Die K&uuml;nstler m&uuml;ssen wieder biologisch und pflanzlich und vegetabil denken k&ouml;nnen. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Das organische Denken - die Entsprechung zum organischen Wachstum - geht in vielen Schichten vor sich. Das ist nicht so einfach, es gibt ja viele Wege, sich an die Natur heranzuarbeiten. Der eine Weg ist, sie abzuzeichnen, so &auml;hnlich wie D&uuml;rer dies getan hat, der andere Weg ist, auf dem Blatt oder auf dem Bild Handlungen zu vollziehen, die dem Wachstum der Pflanzen entsprechen, d.h. man versucht, so zu malen, wie die Pflanze w&auml;chst. Es entsteht etwas aus sich selbst. Und das ist die wahre Sch&ouml;pfung. Wie gesagt, man kann auch Dinge abzeichnen. Unter Abzeichnen verstehe ich nicht nur das photographische Abzeichnen oder das k&uuml;nstlerische Abzeichnen, so &auml;hnlich wie es eben D&uuml;rer gemacht hat, als er ein Rasenst&uuml;ck oder einen Hasen abzeichnete. Das ist nicht photographisch, da ist sehr viel anderes mit dabei. Als Abzeichnen verstehe ich es auch, wenn man seine eigenen Tr&auml;ume abzeichnet, seine innere Welt. Die Surrealisten, also die Wiener Schule versucht, Tr&auml;ume abzuzeichnen bis ins letzte Detail. Man hat eine Vision, man sieht etwas vor Augen, will das verewigen. Das ist auch ein Abzeichnen. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Der n&auml;chste Schritt ist der, da&szlig; man etwas entstehen l&auml;&szlig;t, ganz langsam. Das erfordert nat&uuml;rlich eine gro&szlig;e Konzentration und gelingt auch nur selten. Sehr wichtig ist die Liebe zur Ewigkeit und die Liebe zur Farbe und zum Material. Die Liebe zur Ewigkeit - da mu&szlig; ich wieder von den Pflanzen sprechen. Die Bewegungen der Pflanzen sind ja derartig langsam, da&szlig; man sie nicht mit freiem Auge erkennt, nur mit Hilfe von Zeitraffern. Wenn der K&uuml;nstler schnell malt, so wird das Bild nur so lange halten, als der Augenblick dauerte, in dem er es malte. Der Betrachter des Bildes wird nur einen Augenblick lang daran sein Vergn&uuml;gen haben und sich danach anderen Dingen zuwenden. Ein Augenblicksbild ist so wie ein Blitzlichtphoto. Ein Augenblick herausgenommen, schnell entstanden und schnell vergessen. Je l&auml;ngere Zeitr&auml;ume ein Bild einf&auml;ngt, um so l&auml;nger wird dieses Bild auch bestehen. Man denke da nur an die Mona Lisa von Leonardo da Vinci. Von dem Bild wird gesagt, da&szlig; Leonardo zwanzig, drei&szlig;ig Jahre daran gearbeitet hat, da&szlig; er das Portr&auml;t begonnen hat nach einem jungen M&auml;dchen, das dann langsam eine reife Frau wurde. Vielleicht hat er sogar das Modell gewechselt, oder er hat sich selbst portr&auml;tiert, vielleicht sind in diesem Portr&auml;t die Z&uuml;ge von mehreren Menschen ineinander verwoben - auf alle F&auml;lle ist aber sehr viel Zeit hineingemalt worden. Je langsamer man malt, desto mehr, desto tiefer dringt man in die Geheimnisse der Farbe hinein. Denn Malen ist wie ein Gebet, Malen ist eine religi&ouml;se T&auml;tigkeit. Das kann man nicht rasch verrichten. Es geh&ouml;rt eine gro&szlig;e Andacht dazu, etwas zustande zu bringen. Wer linksh&auml;ndisch und gedankenlos etwas produziert, ist selbst der erste Leidtragende. Damit meine ich aber nicht die Versuche des Tachismus, den Intellekt auszuschlie&szlig;en und die Naturgesetze walten zu lassen, so &auml;hnlich wie es Wols gemacht hat oder Pollock oder teilweise auch Mathieu und Arnulf Rainer. Alle diese Leute haben wirklich mit gro&szlig;er Verantwortung versucht, den Intellekt auszuschalten, indem sie sich z.B. die Augen verbunden haben, indem sie mit der linken Hand malten oder Drogen nahmen. Das ist ein Versuch, sich selbst zu finden. Es ist auch ein drastischer Versuch, sich der Natur anzugleichen, an die Natur heranzukommen.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Jetzt habe ich bereits mehrere Methoden genannt, wie man sich vielschichtig an die Natur heranarbeiten kann. Nat&uuml;rlich gelang es den Tachisten nicht, den Intellekt v&ouml;llig auszuschalten, nur der Tod kann das. Wenn man sozusagen auf die Leiter steigt mit einem Farbtopf, sich oben eine Kugel in den Kopf schie&szlig;t, wenn man dann herunterf&auml;llt mit dem Farbtopf, so wird tats&auml;chlich ein echtes Bild der Natur entstehen. Das hei&szlig;t, dieser Klecks wird dann wirklich den Naturgesetzen entsprechen, und der Mensch hat wirklich wenig damit zu tun gehabt. Wenn der Mensch dagegen auf die Leiter steigt und von oben die Farbe heruntersch&uuml;ttet, so wird zwar ein Fleck entstehen, aber es ist doch etwas anderes. Jedenfalls war das eine sehr gef&auml;hrliche T&auml;tigkeit, und wir m&uuml;ssen dem Tachismus dankbar sein, da&szlig; er uns diese Weisheiten, diesen Markstein und Wendepunkt in der Geschichte der Kunst vermittelt hat, ohne den wir jetzt viel &auml;rmer dastehen w&uuml;rden.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Das n&auml;chste ist die Liebe zur Farbe, die Liebe zum Material. Wenn man die Farbe und das Material, mit dem und auf dem man malt, nicht liebt, dann kann das Bild nichts werden. Es ist v&ouml;llig unm&ouml;glich, da&szlig; man die Farbe, das Papier, die Leinwand und den Pinsel nur als Mittel zum Zweck nimmt. Die Farbe ist ein Lebewesen. Die Farbe ist etwas Heiliges - auch der Pinsel, auch die Leinwand und auch das Papier, auch der Bleistift, was auch immer - man mu&szlig; quasi ein Fetischist all dieser Dinge sein. Man mu&szlig; diese Dinge verehren wie G&ouml;tter. Der Bleistift ist ein Gott, die Farbe ist ein Gott, der Pinsel ist ein Gott. Die Farbe ist wie ein St&uuml;ck Brot, sie ist etwas Heiliges. Genauso wie man Brot nicht wegwerfen und nicht verschwenden darf, darf man Farbe nicht wegwerfen und verschwenden. Man malt nicht willk&uuml;rlich, sondern gezielt, denn man wei&szlig; ganz genau, da&szlig; ein Fehltritt, eine Farbe, die man wegnehmen mu&szlig;, eine Farbe, die man wegschmei&szlig;en mu&szlig;, eine S&uuml;nde ist. Farbe nicht wegzuwerfen bedeutet einerseits Farbe nicht in den M&uuml;ll werfen, also angebrauchte oder auch aufgebrauchte Farbtuben, andererseits aber auch nicht die Leinwand als M&uuml;lleimer zu betrachten, in den man Farbe werfen kann, in dem Gedanken, da&szlig; das sowieso nichts wert ist, weil es eine Studie ist und sowieso weggeworfen wird. Schlechte Farben auf schlechtem Papier, Skizzen auf schlechtem Material, die nachher sowieso weggeworfen werden und sowieso nicht zu halten brauchen.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Die Idee der Skizze ist &uuml;berhaupt etwas ganz Perverses. Skizzen zu machen f&uuml;r etwas, was nachher sein wird, kam ja erst vor ganz kurzer Zeit auf. Ich wei&szlig; nicht, ob vor zwei- oder dreihundert Jahren: In der Menschheitsgeschichte oder auch in der Kunstgeschichte ist das ein winziger Zeitraum. Entweder man machte etwas Gott Wohlgef&auml;lliges, man erschuf etwas, gestaltete etwas, oder eben nicht. Dazu brauchte man nicht vorher eine Skizze oder einen Entwurf. Hat man eine Skizze oder einen Entwurf und macht man das nachher in Gro&szlig; oder Klein oder noch einmal und besser, so geht auf alle F&auml;lle irgend etwas verloren, es sei denn, die Skizze wird ein selbst&auml;ndiges Werk, und das selbst&auml;ndige Werk, das man nachher macht, ist ganz anders als die Skizze. Auch das ist nat&uuml;rlich m&ouml;glich.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Also, keine Farbe wegwerfen! Nicht in den Mistk&uuml;bel werfen, nicht auf die Bilder, auch nicht auf die W&auml;nde ohne &auml;sthetischen Sinn und Zweck schmieren und auch nicht auf die Malkittel, auf die eigene Kleidung oder auf T&uuml;cher und Fetzen wischen! Die Farbe soll so behandelt werden, als w&auml;re sie Euer kostbarstes Gut. Es darf nur so viel Farbe aus der Tube genommen werden, oder so viel Farbe zubereitet werden, als man wirklich verwendet. Ich mache das so, da&szlig; ich die Farbe genau dosiere - lieber etwas weniger als mehr. Habe ich zuviel Farbe zubereitet, dann verwende ich die &uuml;bersch&uuml;ssige Farbe f&uuml;r das n&auml;chste Bild, f&uuml;r ein zweites Bild, das sozusagen in Arbeit ist. Oft male ich mit einer einzigen Farbe tagelang. Ich bereite oft Blau zu und male alles, was blau ist. Nicht jede Farbe ist f&uuml;r alles geeignet. Wenn man die Malerei fr&uuml;herer Jahrhunderte betrachtet, so gab es Farben, die spezifisch f&uuml;r gewisse Zwecke, zum Abbilden gewisser T&ouml;ne, zum Unterlegen gewisser Figuren, f&uuml;r den Himmel oder die Natur bestimmt waren. Das Lapislazuli war nur bestimmt f&uuml;r Kleider, aber nicht f&uuml;r den Himmel. Gewisse Gr&uuml;n hat man nur verwendet als Untermalung f&uuml;r Haut und Fleisch. Es war unm&ouml;glich, da&szlig; der Maler, so wie es heute passiert, irgendein Rot nimmt und es einmal hier- und einmal dorthin schmiert, wie ein Irrer, der im Dunkeln tappt und nicht wei&szlig;, wo er hingeht, da&szlig; er es einmal hier und einmal dorthin schmiert, in der Hoffnung, da&szlig; dann irgendwie eine Einheit entsteht. So entsteht keine Tiefe, keine N&auml;he, es entsteht kein Weitblick und nichts Greifbares, nichts Substantielles. Obwohl oft viele Farben derart verwendet werden, ist das Resultat null und nichtig. Als ich zu malen begann, hatte ich wirklich kein Geld, um Farben zu kaufen, und behalf mir damit - ich war damals nicht an der Akademie -, einfach auf die Akademie zu gehen, um aus den Mistk&uuml;beln die weggeworfenen Farben zu nehmen, seien es Tuben oder Pulver, um sie dann sorgf&auml;ltig aufzubereiten und zu verwenden. Eine weggeworfene Farbtube hatte noch so viel Farbe, da&szlig; ich ein bis zwei Jahre lang damit malen konnte. Man braucht die Tube nur vorsichtig hinten am Schwanz aufklappen und dann mit der Rasierklinge &ouml;ffnen. Hinter dem Tubengewinde ist ein Raum, wo sich noch viel Farbe findet. Auch innerhalb der Tube ist noch so viel Farbe, da werdet Ihr Euch wundern.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Diese Wegwerferei ist eine S&uuml;nde, da mu&szlig; sich etwas &auml;ndern. Der Maler ist ja nicht nur Maler, er mu&szlig; auch &Ouml;kologe sein. Der Maler mu&szlig; ein Revolution&auml;r sein, er mu&szlig; an der Spitze dessen stehen, was der Menschheit vorw&auml;rts hilft, und das geht in unserer heutigen Zeit nicht ohne Natur und ohne &Ouml;kologie. Ohne &ouml;kologisches Bewu&szlig;tsein und ohne Kampf gegen die Wegwerfgesellschaft und die Konsumgesellschaft ist ein positives Schaffen nicht m&ouml;glich.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Es ist v&ouml;llig verfehlt und unter allen Umst&auml;nden abzulehnen, da&szlig; der K&uuml;nstler, der an der vordersten Front des Kampfes um eine bessere Welt stehen sollte, blindlings die Wegwerfgesellschaft imitiert, dadurch da&szlig; er sozusagen ein Konsument von Farben ist, wie die Hausfrau ein Konsument von Waschmittel und die anderen B&uuml;rger Konsumenten von Autos. Der erste Schritt ist eben der, da&szlig; der Maler die Farbe als kostbarstes Gut betrachtet. Teurer und kostbarer als Gold. In fr&uuml;heren Jahrhunderten, bis vor einhundert Jahren etwa, hat die Vorbereitung eines Bildes, des Maluntergrundes l&auml;nger gedauert als das Malen des Bildes selbst. Das Holz, auf dem das Bild gemalt wird, hat hundert Jahre gebraucht um zu wachsen. Es gab Malb&uuml;cher, die das genau beschrieben haben, die Malb&uuml;cher vom Berge Athos, das Malbuch des Malerm&ouml;nches Theophilus und des Italieners Cellini. Es gibt auch moderne B&uuml;cher, die sehr gut sind, wie &quot;Das Malmaterial und seine Verwendung im Bilde&quot; von Doerner und viele andere. Jedenfalls hat man die B&auml;ume, nachdem sie ausgetrocknet waren, gespaltet und - wie man einen Kuchen schneidet - mit der Spitze nach innen zerteilt. Es entstanden Segmente, aus diesen hat man die Malplatten sehr gewissenhaft herausgeschlagen, geschnitzt und geschnitten, mit gr&ouml;&szlig;ter Vorsicht, damit man nicht irgendwelche Venen im Holz st&ouml;rt. Daher ist es kein Wunder, da&szlig; die Malplatten bis auf den heutigen Tag gehalten haben. Heute dagegen nimmt man Holz, s&auml;gt es durch, ohne R&uuml;cksicht auf die Venen und auf die Struktur des Holzes, und wundert sich dann, wenn es nicht h&auml;lt, springt und sich verdreht, sich wirft nach allen m&ouml;glichen Richtungen. Die Vorbereitung des Grundes hat auch sehr lange Zeit in Anspruch genommen, weil auch die Materialien, jahrzehntelang vorbereitet wurden. Der Kalk f&uuml;r Fresken war eine Generation alt, mindestens f&uuml;nfundzwanzig Jahre lag er in der Kalkgrube. Unm&ouml;glich, da&szlig; man Kalk l&ouml;scht und schon verwendet oder mit Pulver anr&uuml;hrt. Je schnellebiger unsere Zivilisation wird, umso schneller wird sie auch zugrunde gehen. Nur wer lange in die Zukunft denkt, der wird auch lange &uuml;berleben. Ich selbst verwende viel Zeit, um Malgr&uuml;nde herzustellen. Ich mu&szlig; sagen, viel mehr als zum Malen selber. Zuerst mu&szlig; man den Rahmen herstellen, also das Chassis. Jetzt geht das so, man kauft irgendein Chassis, steckt es zusammen, spannt etwas drauf oder kauft bereits etwas fix und fertig Bespanntes und malt dann lustig drauf los. Das ist dann so, wie mit den heutigen Kleidern. Vorne ganz sch&ouml;n und hinten ganz h&auml;&szlig;lich. Es soll sich doch jemand die M&uuml;he nehmen, sich auszuziehen, seine Hose, sein Hemd oder den Rock, die Bluse ausziehen und dann Hose und Hemd oder Rock und Bluse von innen nach au&szlig;en st&uuml;lpen und dann verkehrt wieder anziehen. Dann werden Sie sehen, was das f&uuml;r ein Graus ist. Man nehme irgendein Bild, auf dem ein K&uuml;nstler irgendeine geniale Tat vollbringen wollte, drehe das Bild aber um und schaue es von hinten an: Es ist ein absolut entsetzliches Wirrwarr. Da sieht man, wie schlecht das Material ist, wie schlecht das Holz gearbeitet ist. Das Holz ist nicht gebeizt, nicht geformt und nicht geschnitzt. Die Fetzen h&auml;ngen hinten herum. Ich schaue mir immer die R&uuml;ckseite der Bilder an, nur wenn sie hinten sch&ouml;n sind, dann schaue ich sie mir auch vorne an. Interessanterweise sind alle Bilder von den gro&szlig;en Meistern, also der Schule von Siena, von D&uuml;rer, Bruegel hinten genauso sch&ouml;n wie vorne. Man kann die Bilder eigentlich auch von hinten betrachten und ausstellen. Der ehemalige Direktor des Kunsthistorischen Museums, Vincenz Ludwig Oberhammer, hat die Bilder, die in seiner Obhut waren, also die Bruegels, D&uuml;rers und alle anderen aus ungef&auml;hr dieser Epoche so ausgestellt, da&szlig; die Besucher um die Bilder herumgehen und sie von vorne, aber auch von hinten betrachten konnten. Die Bilder wurden direkt in den Raum gestellt, so da&szlig; kein Detail der R&uuml;ckseite dem Betrachter vorenthalten wurde. Die R&uuml;ckseite der Bilder ist eigentlich f&uuml;r den Charakter des Malers ausschlaggebender als die Vorderseite. Deswegen ist es wirklich von Bedeutung, wie das Chassis ausschaut. Das Chassis mu&szlig; optisch und k&uuml;nstlerisch und organisch durchgestaltet werden, in Farbe und Form. Das Chassis mu&szlig; quasi bereits eine Skulptur sein. Auch die Leinwand, die man draufspannt, mu&szlig; perfekt sein. Wenn man sie nicht selbst webt, mu&szlig; sie zumindest mit Liebe aufgezogen werden. Auch die Grundierung soll perfekt sein. Was man unter perfekt versteht, bleibt jedem selbst &uuml;berlassen.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Malen ist eine religi&ouml;se T&auml;tigkeit. Deshalb soll man so gekleidet sein wie bei einem heiligen, sehr feierlichen Anla&szlig;. Das Malen ist etwas sehr Feierliches. Deswegen soll man im Frack erscheinen, im besten Anzug, nicht in einem Arbeitskittel, denn Malen ist ja keine T&auml;tigkeit, bei der man sich schmutzig macht. Malen ist eine T&auml;tigkeit der Andacht, des Ausgewogenseins mit sich und der Welt, des Sich-Findens, des Suchens und der Erleuchtung, der Erkenntnis.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Es ist jetzt Mitternacht geworden in Neuseeland. In Wien ist es zwei Uhr nachmittags. Ich werde jetzt auch schlafen gehen und morgen weitersprechen.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;-*-&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Heute ist der 13. Mai.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Die Aus&uuml;bung der Kunst soll nicht nur eine Eigentherapie sein, d.h. eine Therapie, mit Hilfe derer man selbst gesundet und sich selbst findet, was, wie ich so bei Euch gesehen habe, haupts&auml;chlich der Fall ist. Bei denen, die es ernst meinen, ist es haupts&auml;chlich eine Eigentherapie, d.h. viele von Euch sind verloren und suchen sich und hoffen, sich mit Hilfe der Malerei zu finden. &Uuml;ber diese Eigentherapie hinaus soll die Kunst mehr sein, d.h. nicht dem Maler selbst, sondern der Umwelt etwas geben. Also zuerst mu&szlig; man die Br&uuml;cke zu sich selbst finden, nachher mu&szlig; man die Br&uuml;cke zur Natur und zur Sch&ouml;pfung finden. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Das ist das ganze Geheimnis der Kunst, ein Gleichnis der Kunst, die Br&uuml;cke zur Natur zu finden. Je mehr man sich von der Natur entfernt, desto mehr erleidet die Kunst Schiffbruch. Eines der wichtigsten Geheimnisse der Natur ist, wie sie funktioniert, d.h. wie der Kreislauf funktioniert, der Kreislauf vom Leben zum Sterben. Deswegen habe ich z.B. das Symbol der Spirale gebraucht, das ein Symbol des Lebens und Sterbens ist, des Sich-Ausdehnens und des Sich-Konzentrierens. Das Entstehen aus dem Quasi-Nichts und das Sich-Verlieren in unendliche Weiten, das Entstehen von unendlichen Weiten und das Sterben im kleinsten Punkt. Aber das nur so nebenbei.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Jeder mu&szlig; seinen eigenen Weg finden. Der K&uuml;nstler hat in unserer Gesellschaft die wichtigste Aufgabe zu erf&uuml;llen, nachdem alle anderen Sparten scheinbar Schiffbruch erleiden. Ich meine damit, die G&auml;rtner erleiden Schiffbruch, die &Auml;rzte wissen nicht mehr, was sie tun, die Architekten schaffen ein Chaos, das wir alle kennen, die Urbanisten, die Politiker kennen sich nicht mehr aus, die Priester sind verunsichert und folgen falschen Dogmen. Deswegen hat der K&uuml;nstler daf&uuml;r zu sorgen und dazu beizutragen, da&szlig; die Welt sich erneuert. Was die Menschheit braucht, ist, da&szlig; man ihr einen neuen Weg zeigt. Der neue Weg kann aber nicht h&auml;&szlig;lich sein, wie es leider die zeitgen&ouml;ssische Kunst bisher gezeigt hat. Die zeitgen&ouml;ssische Kunst hat bisher haupts&auml;chlich das Negative aufgezeigt, sie war sozusagen ein Spiegelbild der negativen Auswirkungen unserer Zeit. Die Kunst darf nicht nur Negatives bringen. Die Kunst mu&szlig; warnen, das ist ihre Pflicht, aber sie mu&szlig; gleichzeitig auch einen Ausweg finden. Nur zu warnen und das Negative aufzuzeigen und das Negative wiederzuk&auml;uen, sozusagen im Jammertal zu leben und auch mitzujammern, damit hilft man der Menschheit nicht.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Die Menschen sehnen sich nach Frieden, nach Sch&ouml;nheit, nach Gerechtigkeit und nach dem inneren und dem &auml;u&szlig;eren Frieden. Deswegen kann der K&uuml;nstler nicht nur ganz einfach auf seine eigene Therapie konzentriert sein und schauen, da&szlig; er sich heraush&auml;lt aus der allgemeinen Misere. Er mu&szlig; arbeiten f&uuml;r die anderen, und dann mu&szlig; er seinen Weg zeigen. Der Weg mu&szlig; begehbar sein, und er mu&szlig; sch&ouml;n sein. Deswegen habe ich vor, da&szlig; ein Weg gemacht wird von einem Eingang auf der linken Seite der Akademie in die Klasse, wobei jeder von Euch mithilft, diesen Weg zu gestalten, sei es, eine Stufe zu gestalten, sei es, ein St&uuml;ck Weg mit Mosaik oder Holz am Boden oder an der Wand, einen Weg, den man betreten kann, einen Weg, der sch&ouml;n ist, einen Weg wie durch die Natur, wie durch den Wald, einen gestalteten Weg, wo man verweilen kann, wo man meditieren kann. Diese Akademie wurde vor ungef&auml;hr hundert Jahren oder mehr gebaut und steht jetzt unter Denkmalschutz. An und f&uuml;r sich d&uuml;rften Menschen nicht in H&auml;usern wohnen und t&auml;tig sein, die unter Denkmalschutz stehen. Der Mensch mu&szlig; sich entfalten und entwickeln k&ouml;nnen, gleichzeitig aber das Alte ehren und erhalten. Das ist kein Widerspruch. Das ging bei den alten Kathedralen so, bei den alten Bauwerken, wo man das Alte erhielt und dazubaute oder ganz sachte ver&auml;nderte, ohne es zu zerst&ouml;ren. Das ginge auch hier in dieser Akademie. Es ist nat&uuml;rlich etwas Deprimierendes f&uuml;r jemanden, der sch&ouml;pferisch t&auml;tig sein will und in ein Haus kommt, das fix und fertig ist. Man kann an der Struktur nichts &auml;ndern, dabei ist es doch das Selbstverst&auml;ndlichste, da&szlig; man dem Menschen gestattet, an der Struktur, in der er lebt, in dem Haus, in dem er lebt, etwas zu ver&auml;ndern, also an der Wand, an der Mauer, am Boden, an der Decke, am Fenster, die Licht&ouml;ffnungen zu verbreitern oder zu verkleinern. Deswegen gestaltet Euren Arbeitsbereich! Wenn dieser Arbeitsbereich wie eine Moschee oder ein St&uuml;ck Garten Eden ist, dann glaubt man Euch auch, da&szlig; Ihr f&auml;hig seid, die Umwelt zu gestalten, und dann wird man Euch auch gestatten, gr&ouml;&szlig;ere Dinge in Angriff zu nehmen. Aber zuerst m&uuml;&szlig;t Ihr im Kleinen beginnen.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Der K&uuml;nstler hat die gr&ouml;&szlig;te Aufgabe, daher mu&szlig; er auch die gr&ouml;&szlig;te Verantwortung tragen. Er mu&szlig; die gr&ouml;&szlig;te Intelligenz haben und er mu&szlig; st&auml;rker sein. Er mu&szlig; ein Gigant sein im Gegensatz zu den anderen Berufen, die, wie ich eben ausf&uuml;hrte, v&ouml;llig versagt haben.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Das n&auml;chste ist: Der K&uuml;nstler mu&szlig; unabh&auml;ngig sein. Er mu&szlig; kritisch denken und sch&ouml;pferisch einen positiven Ausweg suchen k&ouml;nnen. Es ist v&ouml;llig falsch, sich einer Tagespolitik hinzugeben, das sind alles Dinge, die vergehen. Um was es heute geht, ist die Haltung der Welt im allgemeinen. Wir m&uuml;ssen einen Friedenspakt mit der Natur schlie&szlig;en. Der K&uuml;nstler ist an einer hervorragenden Position, um diesen Friedenspakt mit der Natur zu bereiten, weil die Kunst eben eine Br&uuml;cke ist zwischen Mensch und Natur. Es geht nicht mehr um kleinliche Streitigkeiten zwischen Menschen, um Religion oder Kapitalismus oder Kommunismus. Das sind l&auml;cherliche Streitigkeiten unter den Menschen, die vom Wesentlichen ablenken, n&auml;mlich unserem Frieden mit der Natur, der unbedingt wiederhergestellt werden mu&szlig;, wenn wir &uuml;berleben wollen.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Das n&auml;chste ist: Die Kunst kann nicht st&auml;ndig unser Jammertal abbilden. Die Kunst mu&szlig; einen Ausweg finden in eine sch&ouml;nere Welt. Die sch&ouml;nen K&uuml;nste m&uuml;ssen sch&ouml;n sein, ansonsten k&ouml;nnen sie nicht existieren. Wenn die sch&ouml;nen K&uuml;nste h&auml;&szlig;lich sind, so ist es keine Kunst. Eine sch&ouml;ne Kunst kann sehr wohl und mu&szlig; sehr wohl kritisch und hart sein und Blut zeigen, aber sie mu&szlig; gleichzeitig Substanz haben und einen gangbaren Weg aufzeigen, den alle beschreiten k&ouml;nnen. Ein Bild mu&szlig; so etwas sein wie eine Kathedrale, wie eine Kapelle, in die man hineingeht, wo man Trost und Zuspruch, aber auch einen Ausweg findet. Ein Weg f&uuml;r alle mu&szlig; gangbar sein, und gangbare Wege sind nur solche, die man gerne geht. Einen h&auml;&szlig;lichen Weg geht man nicht gerne. Nur wenn man gezwungen ist, rennt man zum Beispiel durch Industrieviertel, wo alles gerade ist und wo es stinkt. Das ist ein h&auml;&szlig;licher Weg. Sehr gerne geht man einen geschlungenen Pfad, der baumbestanden ist, aber nicht in Monokultur, sondern mit verschiedenen Gew&auml;chsen der Natur. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Also seid keine Nachvollzieher, rennt nicht irgendwelchen Ideen und irgendwelchen Spielen nach, die andere geschaffen haben, h&auml;ngt Euch nicht an etwas Bestehendes an, sondern schafft selbst von innen heraus. Das k&ouml;nnt Ihr nur, wenn Ihr Euren Ursprung klar legt. Von da aus k&ouml;nnt Ihr dann vorw&auml;rts schreiten. Der K&uuml;nstler mu&szlig; stark sein und selbstbewu&szlig;t, er mu&szlig; sch&ouml;n sein und er mu&szlig; beeindrucken. Das mu&szlig; sich in der Kleidung ausdr&uuml;cken wie auch in Eurer Umgebung, die Ihr gestalten m&uuml;&szlig;t, und auch in Euren Werken. Wenn Ihr auf der Stra&szlig;e geht, mu&szlig; man bereits erkennen, da&szlig; ein Licht, eine Strahlung von Euch ausgeht. Wenn das der Fall ist, dann findet diese St&auml;rke auch ihren Weg auf das Bild, auf die flache Ebene, die Ihr bemalt. Das geht ganz von selber, da braucht man sich gar nicht den Kopf zu zerbrechen oder Qualen erleiden. Es flie&szlig;t dann sozusagen ein m&auml;chtiger Strom direkt auf die Leinwand, man kann das gar nicht eind&auml;mmen.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Ein weiterer Gedankengang ist, da&szlig; man flach malen soll, flach auf dem Tisch und nicht senkrecht auf Staffeleien. Das ist auch eine Vorbereitung auf den Friedensvertrag mit der Natur. Alles, was waagrecht ist, geh&ouml;rt der Natur. Die Natur kann man nur verstehen, wenn man ihr waagrecht begegnet. Das Senkrechte ist die Dom&auml;ne der Menschen. Also alles, was waagrecht ist unter dem freien Himmel, geh&ouml;rt der Natur. Wir haben der Natur widerrechtlich Territorien weggenommen, die wir ihr zur&uuml;ckgeben m&uuml;ssen. Es kann jeder einzelne damit beginnen, indem er ein Bild waagrecht auf den Tisch legt und versucht, ein Gleichnis der Waagrechte der Natur zu schaffen, d. h. ein Bild, das kein Oben und kein Unten hat, sondern das von oben zu betrachten ist. Das ist sozusagen eine Opfergabe an den Himmel, an die Natur, an das Universum. Bilder, die senkrecht sind, Staffeleibilder sind nichts anderes als Spiegel des Unverm&ouml;gens des Menschen. Der Mensch will sich selbst erkennen in dem Bild. Die Staffeleibilder sind mehr oder minder schlecht gemalte Spiegel. Das Staffeleibild ist &uuml;berhaupt erst seit kurzer Zeit in der Menschheitsgeschichte vorhanden.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;PlainText&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Fr&uuml;her gab es &uuml;berhaupt so etwas wie Bilder nicht, es gab auch keine Kunst, denn wenn man eins ist und in Harmonie mit der Natur und Umwelt, dann braucht man keine Kunst, dann ist man selbst Kunst, dann ist man selbst Natur, dann ist man eben in allem, was man tut, im Denken und im Handel und im Wandeln ist man eins mit den ewig g&uuml;ltigen Gesetzen des Kosmos,&nbsp; und man braucht keine Ersatzhandlungen, wie eben die Kunst leider eine ist.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;',
text_occasion_en-'',
text_occasion_ge-'',
text_published_en-'&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Protokolle&lt;/em&gt;. Zeitschrift f&uuml;r Literatur und Kunst. ed. by Otto Breicha, Vol. 2, 1992, Vienna, 1992, pp. 96-116 (German, complete version)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 11pt&quot;&gt;Schmied, Wieland (ed.): Hundertwasser 1928&ndash;2000, Catalogue Raisonn&eacute;. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 11pt&quot;&gt;Vol. I: Schmied, Wieland: Personality, Life, Work. Taschen: &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 11pt&quot;&gt;Cologne&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 11pt&quot;&gt;, 2000, &lt;/span&gt;pp. 31-41. (edited version in German and English)&lt;/p&gt;',
text_published_ge-'&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;protokolle&lt;/em&gt;. Zeitschrift f&uuml;r Literatur und Kunst. hrsg. von Otto Breicha, Bd. 2, Jg. 1992, Wien 1992, S. 96- 116 (in ungek&uuml;rzter Fassung)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Schmied, Wieland (Hg.): Hundertwasser 1928&ndash;2000, Catalogue Raisonn&eacute; &lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;/ Werkverzeichnis. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Vol. II: F&uuml;rst, Andrea Christa:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Catalogue Raisonn&eacute; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;/ Werkverzeichnis. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt;Taschen: K&ouml;ln 2002, S. 31-41 (&lt;/span&gt;gek&uuml;rzte und redigierte Version in&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt&quot;&gt; Deutsch und Englisch)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;',
text_author-'Hundertwasser',
text_orig_lang-'German',
