object(text,'1.4.0.3','RENÉ BRO AND HUNDERTWASSER',[
id-70,
typeOfObject-'TEXT',
text_id-70,
txt-'1.4.0.3',
text_type-'',
text_category-'',
text_title_en-'REN&Eacute; BRO AND HUNDERTWASSER',
text_title_ge-'REN&Eacute; BRO UND HUNDERTWASSER',
text_keywords-'Br&ocirc;, Wandgem&auml;lde, wall painting, collaboration, Zusammenarbeit, Seelenb&auml;ume, soul trees',
text_date-'1950-00-00',
text_summary_en-'',
text_summary_ge-'',
text_language-'en',
text_contents-'&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Collaboration in fine arts is very rare in our egocentered rational and functional society. Every artist wants to be unique in a selfish way. Our days, it is rare that two independent artists join to create a work of art together out of pure enthusiasm.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;I have collaborated with Br&ocirc; in two large murals 96 PARADISE - LAND OF MEN, OF TREES, BIRDS AND SHIPS and 97 THE MIRACULOUS DRAUGHT&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;The second mural 97 THE MIRACULOUS DRAUGHT we decided not to paint directly on the walls but on panels which could be moved away, when the old hunting pavilion in which we painted it would be destroyed which was the case some years later.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;The house was the old hunting pavilion of Napoleon III situated on the border of the Bois de Vincennes in Paris where Napoleon met with his mistress, la comtesse de Castiglione. I lived and painted in this pavilion as guest of the Dumage family for about ten years. When this pavilion was destroyed in the 1960s, the wall on which the mural was painted was cut in pieces by Prof. Licata, then transported to America in a container and reassembled in a Synagogue on Long Island where it is today.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;The mural I painted with Br&ocirc; on pressed fibre board which we carried ourselves through Paris with hand chart. We used the casien-technique which we prepared ourselves. We bought every day fresh milk, let it turn sour and curdle, let the liquid whey drop through a cheesecloth to obtain cottage cheese which we then mixed with unslaked lime.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;This way, we obtained a glue with a strong pungent ammoniac smell with which we mixed the powder colours.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;We divided the work in the way that Br&ocirc; mostly designed the forms like a genius with quickly drawn lines, and I painstakingly coloured between the lines slowly and in tedious work, though Br&ocirc;, from time to time, changed colours himself and I added drawings.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;In that time, I made a deal with Br&ocirc;. Br&ocirc; painted almond-shaped eyes high up in the face with nose, rivers and ship-mouth in circular-shaped heads. I painted soul-trees that means trees which had a halo of glory like human beings and saints. Trees where you could see through as if they were made out of spheres of glass. These trees I had seen in the drawings of Walter Kampmann. Br&ocirc; gave me the right to paint his faces, and I gave Br&ocirc; the right to paint my &ldquo;soul-trees&rdquo;.&lt;/p&gt;',
text_contents_en-'&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Collaboration in fine arts is very rare in our egocentered rational and functional society. Every artist wants to be unique in a selfish way. Our days, it is rare that two independent artists join to create a work of art together out of pure enthusiasm.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;I have collaborated with Br&ocirc; in two large murals 96 PARADISE - LAND OF MEN, OF TREES, BIRDS AND SHIPS and 97 THE MIRACULOUS DRAUGHT&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;The second mural 97 THE MIRACULOUS DRAUGHT we decided not to paint directly on the walls but on panels which could be moved away, when the old hunting pavilion in which we painted it would be destroyed which was the case some years later.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;The house was the old hunting pavilion of Napoleon III situated on the border of the Bois de Vincennes in Paris where Napoleon met with his mistress, la comtesse de Castiglione. I lived and painted in this pavilion as guest of the Dumage family for about ten years. When this pavilion was destroyed in the 1960s, the wall on which the mural was painted was cut in pieces by Prof. Licata, then transported to America in a container and reassembled in a Synagogue on Long Island where it is today.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;The mural I painted with Br&ocirc; on pressed fibre board which we carried ourselves through Paris with hand chart. We used the casien-technique which we prepared ourselves. We bought every day fresh milk, let it turn sour and curdle, let the liquid whey drop through a cheesecloth to obtain cottage cheese which we then mixed with unslaked lime.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;This way, we obtained a glue with a strong pungent ammoniac smell with which we mixed the powder colours.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;We divided the work in the way that Br&ocirc; mostly designed the forms like a genius with quickly drawn lines, and I painstakingly coloured between the lines slowly and in tedious work, though Br&ocirc;, from time to time, changed colours himself and I added drawings.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;In that time, I made a deal with Br&ocirc;. Br&ocirc; painted almond-shaped eyes high up in the face with nose, rivers and ship-mouth in circular-shaped heads. I painted soul-trees that means trees which had a halo of glory like human beings and saints. Trees where you could see through as if they were made out of spheres of glass. These trees I had seen in the drawings of Walter Kampmann. Br&ocirc; gave me the right to paint his faces, and I gave Br&ocirc; the right to paint my &ldquo;soul-trees&rdquo;.&lt;/p&gt;',
text_contents_ge-'&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&Auml;u&szlig;erst selten einmal arbeiten K&uuml;nstler in unserer egozentrischen, rational und funktional ausgerichteten Gesellschaft zusammen. Jeder K&uuml;nstler strebt egoistisch nach Einzigartigkeit. In der heutigen Zeit geschieht es nicht oft, dass sich zwei unabh&auml;ngige K&uuml;nstler zusammentun, um gemeinsam aus reinem Enthusiasmus ein Kunstwerk zu schaffen. Br&ocirc; und ich haben in Zusammenarbeit zwei gro&szlig;e Wandbilder gemalt: 96 &lt;em&gt;Land der Menschen, V&ouml;gel und Schiffe &lt;/em&gt;und 97 &lt;em&gt;Der wunderbare Fischfang&lt;/em&gt;. 96 &lt;em&gt;Paradies - Land der Menschen, V&ouml;gel und Schiffe&lt;/em&gt; haben wir mit Kaseinfarbe direkt auf eine Wand gemalt. Unter dem Einfluss der gro&szlig;en Wandgem&auml;lde in der Toskana (Giotto, Paolo Uccello) und im Palais des Papstes in Avignon wollten wir etwas gleichwertig Phantastisches und Bedeutendes schaffen.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Wir beschlossen, das zweite Wandgem&auml;lde - 97 &lt;em&gt;Der wunderbare Fischfang&lt;/em&gt; - nicht direkt auf die Wand, sondern auf Platten zu malen, die entfernt werden k&ouml;nnten, falls der alte Jagdpavillon, in dem wir malten, abgerissen werden w&uuml;rde, was einige Jahre sp&auml;ter auch tats&auml;chlich geschah. Bei dem Haus handelte es sich um den ehemaligen Jagdpavillon Napoleons III. am Rande des Bois de Vincennes in Paris, wo Napoleon sich mit seiner Maitresse, der Comtesse de Castiglione, traf. Ich lebte und malte als Gast der Familie Dumage ungef&auml;hr zehn Jahre in diesem Pavillon. Als er in den 60er Jahren abgerissen wurde, zerlegte Prof. Licata das Wandgem&auml;lde in Teilst&uuml;cke; diese wurden dann in einem Container nach Amerika transportiert und dort in einer Synagoge auf Long Island wieder zusammengesetzt. Hier befindet es sich auch heute noch.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Br&ocirc; und ich malten auf Pressfaserplatten, die wir eigenh&auml;ndig mit einem Handwagen durch Paris zogen. Wir verwendeten Kaseinfarben, die wir selbst herstellten. Wir kauften jeden Tag frische Milch, lie&szlig;en sie sauer werden, gerinnen und die Molke durch ein Seihtuch abtropfen, um Quark zu erhalten, den wir dann mit ungel&ouml;schtem Kalk mischten.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Das Ergebnis war ein Bindemittel mit starkem, bei&szlig;endem Ammoniakgeruch, das wir wiederum mit den Farbpigmenten mischten.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Wir teilten uns die Arbeit in der Form, dass Br&ocirc; in genialer Weise vor allem die Formen mit schnell gezogenen Linien entwarf, und ich sorgf&auml;ltig die Zwischenr&auml;ume in eint&ouml;niger Kleinarbeit farbig ausmalte, obwohl Br&ocirc; manchmal die Farben &auml;nderte und ich Zeichnungen hinzuf&uuml;gte.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;In dieser Zeit traf ich mit Br&ocirc; eine Vereinbarung. Br&ocirc; malte kreisrunde K&ouml;pfe mit Gesichtern, in denen weit oben mandelf&ouml;rmige Augen sa&szlig;en, mit Nase, Fl&uuml;ssen und einem Mund in der Form eines Schiffes. Ich malte &bdquo;Seelen-B&auml;ume&ldquo;, die wie Menschen oder Heilige von einer Aureole umgeben waren. B&auml;ume, durch die man hindurchsehen konnte, als k&auml;men sie aus gl&auml;sernen Welten. Diese B&auml;ume hatte ich in den Zeichnungen Walter Kampmanns gesehen. Br&ocirc; erlaubte mir, seine Gesichter zu zeichnen, und er durfte meine &bdquo;Seelen-B&auml;ume&ldquo; malen.&lt;/p&gt;',
text_occasion_en-'Manuscript for a contribution to the Catalogue of the exhibition &bdquo;Collaboration in Art&ldquo;, Hirshhorn Museum, Washington',
text_occasion_ge-'Manuskript f&uuml;r einen Beitrag im Kat. Der Ausstellung &bdquo;Collaboration in Art&ldquo;, Hirshhorn Museum, Washington DC',
text_published_en-'',
text_published_ge-'',
text_author-'Hundertwasser',
text_orig_lang-'',
text_translator-'',
text_source_en-'',
text_source_ge-'&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;',
text_excerpt-'',
text_origin-''
]).

%Andrea###2009-06-26 07:25:11###object###text###1.4.1.1
object(text,'1.4.1.1','THREE POSTAGE STAMPS FOR SENEGAL',[
id-124,
typeOfObject-'TEXT',
text_id-124,
txt-'1.4.1.1',
text_type-'',
text_category-'',
text_title_en-'THREE POSTAGE STAMPS FOR SENEGAL',
text_title_ge-'',
text_keywords-'',
text_date-'1979-03-23',
text_summary_en-'',
text_summary_ge-'',
text_language-'en',
text_contents-'I have loved postage stamps long before I became a painter. It was a big joy to collect these little coloured pictures, to separate them from the letters which came from far away, with the steam coming out of the exhaust pipe of a teapot if I did not want t soak the whole envelop in water. Then I put the stamps between the pages of a book to dry them. I remember very well this philatelistic activity at the time when Vienna was occupied by the Soviet Union. I experienced a strange happiness at the end of the war, in May 1945 when I made order in my stamps while the soldiers of the Red Army heaped on lorries passed in front of my open windows singing Russian songs. I even wrote a poem to the glory of postage stamps while I was in grammar school. I had a big correspondance with stamp collector-friends the world over, in so far away and exotic countries like India, The U.S.A., Switzerland, Morocco, Ireland and many others. I simply wrote &ldquo;to an unknown stamp collector&rdquo; in an interesting sounding town in a distant country which I looked up in my atlas of the world. From about 3 letters I sent I got one answer. Then we exchanged postage stamps inside the letters and glued on top of the envelops for many years. It was like a prelud to may later activity as a painter with my exhibitions around the world. In fact, the postage stamps awakened my desire to become a painter &ndash; to be able to create myself little beautiful pictures full of colour and life, just like the postage stamps, and to conquer the world with it. And for a long time I was unhappy and unsatisfied with myself because the pictures I painted could not stand the comparison with postage stamps. This happened when I was between 10 and 17 years of age. Postage stamps have always been sacred objects to me. The men who created them were almost like gods to me, much more inaccessible then the kings of this world. The stamps and those who made them were for me the real ambassadors of this earth, the real representatives of the world parliament. The small pictures I can carry with me in small books. They are like venerable objects, like icons. You imagine wonderful worlds and you dream. I exchanged the stamps I liked less or which I had twice against other stamps I did not have and which shone in all colours. I could see all details with the magnifying glass. Therefore, I am proud that I am allowed to create postage stamps for Senegal, a far away and exotic country which I love. And for my stamps I can use all my knowledge and experience as a painter which I accumulated when discovering my phantastic kingdoms. And the wonderful dreams of my early age are reaching a much more wonderful reality because they are crystallized dreams of a world from beyond which came true in small pictures which you can see and touch and glue on letters and send from one distant land to another distant land. And the biggest joy for me is that I can collect myself Hundertwasser stamps which I can put next to the other beautiful ones I already have. It is my wish that my postage stamps may honour President L&eacute;opold S&eacute;dar Senghor and Senegal. ',
text_contents_en-'I have loved postage stamps long before I became a painter. It was a big joy to collect these little coloured pictures, to separate them from the letters which came from far away, with the steam coming out of the exhaust pipe of a teapot if I did not want t soak the whole envelop in water. Then I put the stamps between the pages of a book to dry them. I remember very well this philatelistic activity at the time when Vienna was occupied by the Soviet Union. I experienced a strange happiness at the end of the war, in May 1945 when I made order in my stamps while the soldiers of the Red Army heaped on lorries passed in front of my open windows singing Russian songs. I even wrote a poem to the glory of postage stamps while I was in grammar school. I had a big correspondance with stamp collector-friends the world over, in so far away and exotic countries like India, The U.S.A., Switzerland, Morocco, Ireland and many others. I simply wrote &ldquo;to an unknown stamp collector&rdquo; in an interesting sounding town in a distant country which I looked up in my atlas of the world. From about 3 letters I sent I got one answer. Then we exchanged postage stamps inside the letters and glued on top of the envelops for many years. It was like a prelud to may later activity as a painter with my exhibitions around the world. In fact, the postage stamps awakened my desire to become a painter &ndash; to be able to create myself little beautiful pictures full of colour and life, just like the postage stamps, and to conquer the world with it. And for a long time I was unhappy and unsatisfied with myself because the pictures I painted could not stand the comparison with postage stamps. This happened when I was between 10 and 17 years of age. Postage stamps have always been sacred objects to me. The men who created them were almost like gods to me, much more inaccessible then the kings of this world. The stamps and those who made them were for me the real ambassadors of this earth, the real representatives of the world parliament. The small pictures I can carry with me in small books. They are like venerable objects, like icons. You imagine wonderful worlds and you dream. I exchanged the stamps I liked less or which I had twice against other stamps I did not have and which shone in all colours. I could see all details with the magnifying glass. Therefore, I am proud that I am allowed to create postage stamps for Senegal, a far away and exotic country which I love. And for my stamps I can use all my knowledge and experience as a painter which I accumulated when discovering my phantastic kingdoms. And the wonderful dreams of my early age are reaching a much more wonderful reality because they are crystallized dreams of a world from beyond which came true in small pictures which you can see and touch and glue on letters and send from one distant land to another distant land. And the biggest joy for me is that I can collect myself Hundertwasser stamps which I can put next to the other beautiful ones I already have. It is my wish that my postage stamps may honour President L&eacute;opold S&eacute;dar Senghor and Senegal. ',
text_contents_ge-'  &lt;p style=&quot;line-height: 150%&quot; class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;letter-spacing: 0.4pt&quot;&gt;Briefmarken habe ich sehr geliebt, lange bevor ich Maler wurde. F&uuml;r mich war es ein gro&szlig;es Gl&uuml;ck, die kleinen bunten Bilder zu sammeln, die von weither kamen, und sie abzul&ouml;sen von den Briefumschl&auml;gen mit dem Dampfauspuff einer Teekanne, wenn ich nicht den ganzen Briefumschlag ins Wasser legen wollte. Nachher habe ich die Briefmarken zum Trocknen zwischen Buchseiten gelegt &lt;/span&gt;&middot; &lt;span style=&quot;letter-spacing: 0.4pt&quot;&gt;Ich erinnere mich sehr genau an diese Besch&auml;ftigung, als Wien noch von sowjetischen Truppen besetzt war, im Mai 1945. Ich versp&uuml;rte ein seltsames Hochgef&uuml;hl, als ich die Briefmarken ordnete und noch einmal ordnete, w&auml;hrend vor meinen offenen Fenstern die Soldaten der Roten Armee auf Lastwagen gepfercht vorbeifuhren und russische Lieder sangen. Ich habe auch im Realgymnasium ein Gedicht zur Ehre der Briefmarken geschrieben &lt;/span&gt;&middot; &lt;span style=&quot;letter-spacing: 0.4pt&quot;&gt;Ich hatte einen umfangreichen Briefwechsel mit Briefmarkenfreunden in der ganzen Welt, in so exotischen L&auml;ndern wie Indien, der Schweiz, Amerika und Marokko, Irland und vielen anderen L&auml;ndern &lt;/span&gt;&middot; &lt;span style=&quot;letter-spacing: 0.4pt&quot;&gt;Ich schrieb ganz einfach Briefe an &raquo;einen unbekannten Briefmarkensammler&laquo; in einer exotisch klingenden Stadt, die ich im Weltatlas heraussuchte, in einem fernen Land, und bekam etwa auf drei Briefe eine Antwort. Dann schickten wir uns gegenseitig Briefmarken im Brief und auf dem Umschlag, jahrelang &middot;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;letter-spacing: 0.4pt&quot;&gt;Es war ein Vorspiel zu meiner heutigen Aktivit&auml;t als Maler mit Ausstellungen in der ganzen Welt &middot; Tats&auml;chlich haben die Briefmarken in mir den Wunsch geweckt, Maler zu werden. Ich wollte auch so kleine Bilder malen, so bunt, so voll Leben, so sch&ouml;n wie die Briefmarken, und damit die Welt erobern &lt;/span&gt;&middot; &lt;span style=&quot;letter-spacing: 0.4pt&quot;&gt;Und lange war ich ungl&uuml;cklich und unzufrieden, weil die Bilder, die ich malte, den Vergleich mit den Briefmarken nicht aushielten &middot; Das war, als ich zehn bis siebzehn Jahre alt war.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p style=&quot;line-height: 150%&quot; class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;letter-spacing: 0.4pt&quot;&gt;Die Briefmarke war f&uuml;r mich immer ein heiliger Gegenstand. Die Menschen, die sie machten, waren f&uuml;r mich Halbg&ouml;tter, viel unerreichbarer als die K&ouml;nige dieser Erde &lt;/span&gt;&middot; &lt;span style=&quot;letter-spacing: 0.4pt&quot;&gt;Die Briefmarken und ihre Sch&ouml;pfer waren f&uuml;r mich die wahren Botschafter dieser Erde, die wahren Abgeordneten eines Weltparlamentes &lt;/span&gt;&middot; &lt;span style=&quot;letter-spacing: 0.4pt&quot;&gt;Die kleinen Bilder kann man bei sich tragen, in kleinen B&uuml;chern. Sie sind wie Kultobjekte, wie Ikonen. Man stellt sich phantastische Weiten vor und tr&auml;umt &lt;/span&gt;&middot; &lt;span style=&quot;letter-spacing: 0.4pt&quot;&gt;Man tauscht die Briefmarken, die man doppelt hat und die, die einem weniger gefallen, gegen andere, die in allen Farben leuchten. Man kann jedes Detail mit der Lupe sehen. Und noch dazu kann ich all die wunderbaren Landschaften, die ich ein ganzes Leben lang als Maler entdeckt habe, in den Briefmarken auferstehen lassen. So werden die wundersch&ouml;nen Tr&auml;ume meiner Jugend zu einer noch wunderbareren Wirklichkeit, weil es zu Kristall gewordene Tr&auml;ume sind, Bilder einer jenseitigen Welt, die sich realisiert haben, erstarrt in kleinen Bildern, die man richtig sehen und ber&uuml;hren kann und aufkleben auf Briefe und von einem fernen Land in ein anderes fernes Land senden kann &lt;/span&gt;&middot; &lt;span style=&quot;letter-spacing: 0.4pt&quot;&gt;Und die allergr&ouml;&szlig;te Freude f&uuml;r mich ist die, da&szlig; ich selbst Hundertwasser-Briefmarken sammeln und neben die anderen sch&ouml;nen, die ich schon besitze, einreihen kann.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;letter-spacing: 0.3pt&quot;&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  ',
text_occasion_en-'&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;3&quot;&gt;&lt;font face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;&gt;Written in Vienna on 23 March 1979 on occasion of the publishing of his three postage stamps for the Republic of Senegal.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;',
text_occasion_ge-'  &lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Geschrieben anl&auml;sslich der Herausgabe seiner drei Briefmarken f&uuml;r die Republik Senegal im Jahr 1979.&lt;/p&gt;  ',
text_published_en-'&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;3&quot; face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;&gt;brochure by &raquo;Office des Postes et Telecommunications du Senegal&laquo;, Dakar/Senegal, 1979&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;3&quot; face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;&gt; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;3&quot;&gt;&lt;font face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;&gt;Catalogues of the World Travelling Museum Exhibition: &lt;u&gt;English edition:&lt;/u&gt; London, 1983. &lt;u&gt;German edition:&lt;/u&gt; Cologne, 1980; Vienna, Graz, 1981&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;3&quot; face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;&gt; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;3&quot;&gt;&lt;font face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;&gt;Schurian, Walter (ed.): Hundertwasser &ndash; Sch&ouml;ne Wege, Gedanken &uuml;ber Kunst und Leben. (Beautiful Paths &ndash; Thoughts on Art and Life) Deutscher Taschenbuch Verlag (dtv): Munich, 1983, pp. 72-73 and ed. 2004 (Langen M&uuml;ller Verlag, Munich), pp. 335-336 (German)&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;',
text_published_ge-'  &lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Brosch&uuml;re des &raquo;Office des Postes et Telecommunications du Senegal&laquo;, Dakar/Senegal 1979&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Kataloge zur Welt-Wanderausstellung: &lt;u&gt;Englische Ausgabe:&lt;/u&gt; London, 1983. &lt;u&gt;Deutsche Ausgabe:&lt;/u&gt; K&ouml;ln, 1980; Wien, Graz, 1981&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Schurian, Walter (Hg.): Hundertwasser &ndash; Sch&ouml;ne Wege, Gedanken &uuml;ber Kunst und Leben. Deutscher Taschenbuch Verlag (dtv): M&uuml;nchen 1983, S. 72-73 und Ausgabe 2004 (Langen M&uuml;ller Verlag, M&uuml;nchen), S. 335-336&lt;/p&gt;  ',
text_author-'Hundertwasser',
text_orig_lang-'',
text_translator-'',
text_source_en-'',
text_source_ge-'',
text_excerpt-'',
text_origin-''
]).

